半导体基本指南
作者： Jim Turley
 
发行商 : 普伦蒂斯霍尔 PTR
发布日期 ：2002 年 12 月 19 日
国际标准书号 ：0-13-046404-X
页面 ：239

 

 

 

 

《半导体基本指南》是一本完整的专业指南，介绍半导体设计和制造的业务和技术。领先的半导体行业分析师兼编辑 Jim Turley 阐明了该行业的方方面面，简单、清晰地解释了该行业的快速变化的技术、市场和商业模式，没有不必要的术语。

The Essential Guide to Semiconductors is a complete professional's guide to the business andtechnology of semiconductor design and manufacturing. Leading semiconductor industry analystand editor Jim Turley illuminates every facet of the industry, explaining its fast-changingtechnologies, markets, and business models simply, clearly, and without unnecessary jargon.

  • 涵盖广泛的半导体应用：手机、汽车、电脑、游戏系统等等

  • Covers a wide range of semiconductor applications: cellphones, cars, computers, gaming systems, and much more

  • 对于普通人和非技术投资者来说，概念性足够强；对于技术读者来说，内容足够详细

  • Conceptual enough for laypeople and nontechnical investorsand sufficiently detailed for technical readers

  • 包括各种图表和流程图以促进理解

  • Includes a wide range of diagrams and flowcharts to promote understanding

  • 以通俗易懂的方式讲解硅芯片的设计和制造方法

  • Presents accessible explanations of how silicon chips are designed and built

  • 展示整个行业如何协同运作，帮助读者了解关键的细分市场、细分市场和机会

  • Shows how the entire industry fits together, helping readers understand key niches, market segments, and opportunities

      关于 Prentice Hall 专业技术参考

      About Prentice Hall Professional Technical Reference

      Prentice Hall Professional Technical Reference (PH PTR) 的起源可追溯到 20 世纪 60 年代业界首个计算机科学出版项目，如今已发展成为全球领先的技术书籍提供商。Prentice Hall Professional Technical Reference (PH PTR) 于 1986 年正式以独立出版社的身份推出，目前每年出版 200 多本书籍，作者均为计算机、工程和商业领域的领军人物。

      With origins reaching back to the industry's first computer science publishing program in the 1960s, Prentice Hall Professional Technical Reference (PH PTR) has developed into the leading provider of technical books in the world today. Formally launched as its own imprint in 1986, our editors now publish over 200 books annually, authored by leaders in the fields of computing, engineering, and business.

      我们的根基牢牢扎根在技术革命兴起的土壤中。我们的书架上有许多业界的计算和工程经典著作：Kernighan 和 Ritchie 的《C 编程语言》、Nemeth 的《UNIX 系统管理手册》、Horstmann 的《核心 Java》和 Johnson 的《高速数字设计》。

      Our roots are firmly planted in the soil that gave rise to the technological revolution. Our bookshelf contains many of the industry's computing and engineering classics: Kernighan and Ritchie's C Programming Language, Nemeth's UNIX System Administration Handbook, Horstmann's Core Java, and Johnson's High-Speed Digital Design.

      PH PTR 承认其良好的开端，同时展望未来以寻求灵感。我们通过为当今的专业人士提供未来的解决方案，不断发展并在出版领域开辟新天地。

      PH PTR acknowledges its auspicious beginnings while it looks to the future for inspiration. We continue to evolve and break new ground in publishing by providing today's professionals with tomorrow's solutions.

        谁会在电影结束时读出演职员表？

        Who reads the credits at the end of a movie?

        当然是那些被点名的人。他们努力工作，却只得到一些小字。很多人花了和我差不多多的时间在这本书上，但可能没有那么喜欢。我很感激他们，因为他们的努力让这本书变得更好。如果还有任何错误或遗漏，那都是我的错。

        The people who are named, of course. They worked hard and all they get is some small print. Lots of people spent nearly as much time on this book as I did, but probably enjoyed it less. I'm indebted to them because all of their efforts made it better. If any errors or omissions remain, that's all my work.

        本书中的许多图片和照片均由以下人员提供：Nick Tredennick（Dynamic Silicon）；Integrated Device Technology 的 Lindsay Okamoto 和 Phil Bourekas；德州仪器的 Susanna Jakubik、Gary Silcott 和 Henry Wiechman；日立的 PF Domanis 和 Akiko Ishiyama；Sun Microsystems 的 Nancy Snyder、Rosalind Yeh 和 Martin Chorich；以及 ASM Lithography 的 Michelle Herrick。感谢您在这么短的时间内赶来工作。

          第 1 章 良好的开端

          Chapter 1. Running Start

          在本章中...

          In this chapter...

          • 关于本书

          • About This Book

          • 一些需要了解的词语

          • Some Words to Know

          很少有东西能像半导体的发现那样改变现代生活，在人们的记忆中肯定没有。现代电子产品彻底改变了我们彼此交谈的方式以及我们交谈的对象。它改变了医学研究、娱乐、记录保存、旅行和探索。自过去 50 年固态电子器件问世以来，几乎没有任何企业、职业或行业没有发生变化。

          Few things have altered modern life as much as the discovery of semiconductors, and certainly none in living memory. Modern electronics have completely changed the way we talk with each other and who we talk with. It has changed medical research, entertainment, record keeping, travel, and exploration. There's almost no business, profession, or industry that hasn't changed since the introduction of solid-state electronics in the last 50 years.

          计算机只是整个电子行业的开始。个人电脑和其他类型的计算机通常被视为整个电子行业的标志，但世界上只有不到一半的电子产品用于任何类型的计算机。它们中的大多数用于更普通但可能更有用的产品，如恒温器、汽车防抱死制动系统、空调、电视、X 射线扫描仪、收音机和手机。现代电子产品的日常、不为人知的影响使其无处不在，并成为我们生活中不可或缺的一部分。

          Computers are only the beginning of it. PCs and other types of computers are often made the figurehead for the entire electronics industry, but less than half of the world's electronics are used in computers of any kind. Most of them go into more mundane, but probably more useful products like thermostats, automobile antilock brake systems, air conditioning, televisions, x-ray scanners, radios, and cellular telephones. It's the everyday, little-seen effects of modern electronics that make it so ubiquitous and so much a part of our lives.

          晶体管是现代电子产品的基本组成部分之一，随着晶体管收音机的推出，晶体管在 20 世纪 60 年代变得家喻户晓。2001 年，半导体行业为地球上每个男人、女人和孩子生产了约 6000 万个晶体管。到 2010 年，这一数字预计将达到人均约 10 亿个晶体管。这些曾经的科学奇迹，如今已经变得比大米还丰富。

          One of the basic building blocks of modern electronics is the transistor, a device that became a household word in the 1960s with the introduction of transistor radios. In 2001, the semiconductor industry manufactured about 60 million transistors for every man, woman, and child on Earth. By 2010, this number is expected to be about 1 billion transistors per capita. Once scientific marvels, these tiny flakes of silicon have now become more plentiful than rice.

            关于本书

            About This Book

            好奇是正常的，因为我们的日常生活与祖父母的日常生活有着根本的区别。然而，电子、半导体和芯片制造的本质是技术性的，说实话，对于非工程师来说，这相当枯燥。我们如何才能跟上这个快速发展的行业，而不成为书呆子呢？

            It's normal to be curious about something that so fundamentally separates our daily lives from those of our grandparents. However, the nature of electronics, semiconductors, and chip making is inherently technical and, to be honest, pretty dull to the nonengineer. How can we keep up with this fast-moving business without becoming a nerd?

            许多人在未成为飞行员的情况下驾驶飞机。许多人在未拥有航海经验的情况下驾驶轮船或渡轮。您无需成为机械师即可驾驶汽车。同样，许多人在庞大的电子和半导体行业工作，但未获得工程学位。本书面向他们：好奇、聪明的成年人，他们希望了解这个无限迷人的行业、科学和技术背后的术语、词汇和概念。

            Plenty of people fly in airplanes without being pilots. Lots of people sail on ships or ride ferries without nautical experience. You can drive a car without being a mechanic. By the same token, plenty of people work in the massive electronics and semiconductor industries without first earning engineering degrees. This book is intended for them: the curious, intelligent adults who want a primer on the terms, words, and concepts behind this endlessly fascinating business, science, and technology.

            虽然本书的章节结构合理，但您不必按顺序阅读，甚至不必全部阅读。有些章节是成对的，最好一起阅读，例如第3章和第 4章，它们介绍了硅芯片的设计和制造方法。一般来说，您可以随意浏览，让您的好奇心带您去任何地方。

            Although this book is organized logically into a progression of chapters, it's not necessary to read them in order, or even to read them all. Some chapters are paired and might be best read together, such as Chapters 3 and 4, which deal with how silicon chips are designed and built. In general, feel free to browse and let your curiosity take you where it may.

            我刻意避免在本书中使用专业术语、流行语和缩略语。在本书的后面，你会发现一个词汇表，它定义了这个行业中常见的许多三个字母的缩略语 (TLA)，即使这些术语从未在本书中使用过。如果没有其他用途，请将词汇表放在书签中，以便在需要时可以快速查阅。

            I have made a deliberate attempt to avoid jargon, buzzwords, and acronyms through this book. In the back you'll find a glossary that defines many of the three-letter acronyms (TLAs) common to this business, even if those terms are never used in this book. If nothing else, keep a bookmark in the glossary so you can turn to it quickly in time of need.

              一些需要了解的词语

              Some Words To Know

              大多数企业都有自己的专业词汇，外行人无法理解。水管工、医生、矿工和飞行员都使用我们其他人不懂的单词和短语。芯片制造商和设计师也是如此。他们的大多数专业术语对我们来说并不感兴趣，但其中一些词已经渗透到一般用法中。我将在本书中根据需要定义其他词。

              Most businesses have their own specialized vocabulary that's impenetrable to outsiders. Plumbers, doctors, miners, and pilots all use words and phrases that the rest of us don't understand. It's the same with chip makers and designers. Most of their professional lingo isn't of interest to us here, but some of these words have leaked into general usage. I'll define others throughout this book as we need them.

              什么是芯片？

              What's a Chip?

              您肯定已经听过与半导体相关的最常见单词是芯片，例如硅芯片、内存芯片或计算机芯片。芯片是经过精心加工的小硅片，它们可以发挥惊人的作用。有数百万种不同类型的芯片用于手机、防抱死制动系统、电视、收音机和无数其他设备。内存芯片和微处理器都是芯片的例子。无论大小，所有芯片的制造方式都大致相同，由相同的基本材料即硅和铝制成。

              The most common word you've undoubtedly already heard related to semiconductors is chip, as in silicon chip, memory chip, or computer chip. Chips are little flakes of silicon that have been carefully worked on in such a way that they do amazing things. There are millions of different kinds of chips made for cell phones, antilock brake systems, televisions, radios, and innumerable other devices. Memory chips and microprocessors are both examples of chips. Big or small, all chips are made in more or less the same way, from the same basic materials, namely silicon and aluminum.

              什么是硅？

              What's Silicon?

              硅是一种非常普通的物质：它是沙子。信不信由你，世界上所有先进的硅芯片基本上都是用沙子制成的。无论这些芯片用于计算机、卫星、手机、视频游戏还是家用恒温器，它们都起源于某个海滩。（从技术上讲，工业级硅是专门制造的，不是用桶从海滩上捞出来的，但不管怎样，它们都是同样的东西。）

              Silicon is a perfectly normal substance: It's sand. Believe it or not, all the world's advanced silicon chips are basically made out of sand. Whether the chips are used in computers, satellites, cell phones, video games, or household thermostats, they all have the same humble beginnings on a beach somewhere. (Technically, industrial-grade silicon is specially manufactured, not scooped off the beach with a pail, but it's the same stuff either way.)

              这里有一点需要记住：silicone和silicone不一样。silicone 与“drawn”押韵，是制作芯片的沙质材料。silicone 与“throne”押韵，是整形外科医生使用的材料。您还可以在五金店找到硅脂；它可以起到良好的防风雨作用，并能防止铰链吱吱作响。这两个词如此接近，这是英语的一个不幸的伎俩。它们真的没有任何共同之处，也完全没有关系。如果你不小心提到“silicone chips”，你肯定会被打上业余的标签。

              Here is one important point to remember: silicon is not the same as silicone. Silicon rhymes with "drawn" and is the sandy stuff chips are made of. Silicone rhymes with "throne" and is the stuff that cosmetic surgeons use. You can also find silicone grease at the hardware store; it makes good weatherproofing and stops squeaky hinges. It's an unfortunate trick of the English language that these two words are so close together. They really have nothing in common and are not related at all. You're sure to mark yourself as an amateur if you accidentally mention "silicone chips."

              硅谷当然是加利福尼亚州圣克拉拉山谷的昵称。它位于旧金山（北端）和圣何塞（南端）之间，长约 50 英里。那里没有天然硅，但从一些居民的判断来看，那里有相当数量的硅。

              Silicon Valley, of course, is the nickname for the Santa Clara Valley of California. It's a roughly 50-mile stretch between San Francisco (at the north end) and San Jose (at the south end). There's no natural silicon there, although judging from some of the inhabitants, there is a fair amount of silicone.

              什么是半导体？

              What's a Semiconductor?

              半导体这个词其实只有化学家才会用。它指的是一种能导电但导电性不是很好的化学物质或物质。有些材料，比如铜，导电性很好。这就是为什么房子是用铜线建造的。其他材料，比如橡胶和塑料，根本不导电。这就是为什么电源线外面是塑料的：为了保护我们免受里面电的伤害。最后，还有第三类材料，半导体，它的导电性比塑料好，但不如铜。出于不必解释的原因，这使得半导体成为制造芯片的绝佳材料，而硅是目前最好的半导体之一。

              Semiconductor is a word that only chemists should really be using. It means a chemical or a substance that conducts electricity, but not very well. Some materials, like copper, conduct electricity quite well. That's why houses are built with copper wires. Other materials, like rubber and plastic, don't conduct electricity at all. That's why power cords are plastic on the outside: to protect us from the electricity inside. Finally, there's a third class of materials, the semiconductors, that conduct electricity better than plastic but not as well as copper. For reasons it's not important to explain, this makes semiconductors great materials for building chips, and silicon is one of the best semiconductors available.

              我们还使用“半导体”一词来指代由硅制成的物品（见图1.1）。例如，在本书中，您将阅读有关计算机芯片“和其他半导体”的内容。这并不意味着硅以外的材料。它指的是由硅制成的制造物品。从这个意义上讲，半导体基本上与芯片或组件相同。

              We also use the word semiconductor to refer to things made from silicon (see Figure 1.1). For example, in this book you'll read about computer chips "and other semiconductors." That doesn't mean materials other than silicon. It means manufactured items that are made from silicon. In that sense, semiconductor is basically the same as chip or component.

              图 1.1。几乎所有电子设备都是由纯化的硅（沙子）制成的。硅被加工成各种不同的形状和设计，以制造芯片和其他组件。芯片种类繁多，其他类型的组件也多种多样。

              并非所有半导体都是芯片；赌场经营者可能会说并非所有芯片都是半导体。这一类别中唯一的另一个好笑话涉及一位工作时间被削减的铁路乘务员：他成为了半导体。

              Not all semiconductors are chips; casino operators might say not all chips are semiconductors, either. The only other good joke in this category involves a railroad conductor who had his hours cut back: He became a semiconductor.

              什么是晶体管？

              What's a Transistor?

              每个人都听说过晶体管收音机（至少是某个年龄段的人），但有多少人知道晶体管到底是什么？它是大事还是小事？是好事还是坏事？这些问题的答案既少又好。

              Everybody has heard of a transistor radio (at least, everyone of a certain age), but how many know what a transistor really is? Is it a big thing or a little thing? Good or bad? The answers to these questions are little and good.

              晶体管是大多数电子产品中最小、最基本的构件。它们是建造高耸入云的塔楼的砖块。晶体管可以组合起来制造出电子工程师能想到的几乎任何东西。电子工程师可能会将一天的工作描述为 5,000 个晶体管的电路，就像厨师对三个鸡蛋的煎蛋卷充满热情一样。

              Transistors are the smallest, most basic building blocks in most electronics. They are the bricks from which the soaring towers are made. Transistors can be combined to make nearly anything an electrical engineer can imagine. An electrical engineer might describe a day's work as a 5,000-transistor circuit the way a cook might enthuse over a three-egg omelet.

              晶体管可以做大做小，但主流趋势是让它们变得更小。第一个晶体管诞生于 20 世纪 50 年代，只有拇指那么大。现代晶体管的直径约为百万分之一英寸。你可以毫不知情地吸入一千个晶体管。你的指甲上也可以装下超过 1000 万个晶体管，在第 4章中，我们将看到这些现代奇迹是如何组装起来的。

              Transistors can be made as big or as small as you like, but the overwhelming trend is to make them smaller. The first transistors, created in the 1950s, were as big as your thumb. Modern transistors arehold your breathabout one-millionth of an inch across. You could easily inhale a thousand transistors and not know it. You can also fit more than 10 million transistors on your fingernail, and in Chapter 4 we'll see exactly how these modern miracles are put together.

              什么是 IC？

              What's an IC?

              IC（集成电路）只是芯片的另一个术语。您可以互换使用IC和芯片这两个术语。

              IC (integrated circuit) is just another term for a chip. You can use the terms IC and chip interchangeably.

              什么是组件？

              What's a Component?

              元件与芯片类似，但这个术语的含义更广泛一些。所有芯片都是元件，但并非所有元件都是芯片。几乎任何用硅制成的电气设备都是元件。芯片是最常见的元件类型，但也有其他类型的电气元件，如电阻器和电容器。

              A component is similar to a chip, but the term is a little broader. All chips are components, but not all components are chips. Pretty much any electrical type of device you might make from silicon is a component. Chips are the most common type of component, but there are other types of electrical components, too, like resistors and capacitors.

              什么是电路？

              What's a Circuit?

              电路是一个中等强度的技术术语，用于描述电子设计。建筑师绘制蓝图，电气工程师设计电路。对于这些人来说，电流总是以圆圈的形式流动，就像马在赛道上奔跑一样。因此，任何电子设计都称为电路。无论是大型设计（如整台电视）还是小型设计（如单个芯片），它仍然被称为电路。在本书中，您将看到电路被用作许多不同类型的电气设计的统称。

              Circuit is a medium-strength technical word to describe an electronic design. Architects create blueprints; electrical engineers create circuits. To these people, electricity always travels in a circle, like horses around a track. Therefore, any electronic design is called a circuit. Whether it's a big design (like an entire television) or a small design (like a single chip), it's still called a circuit. In this book, you'll see circuit used as a catch-all term for many different kinds of electrical designs.

                第 2 章 半导体家族树

                Chapter 2. Semiconductor Family Tree

                在本章中...

                In this chapter...

                • 半导体家族树

                • Semiconductor Family Tree

                • 简单的模拟元件

                • Simple Analog Components

                • 高级模拟元件

                • Advanced Analog Components

                • A/D 和 D/A 转换器

                • A/D and D/A Converters

                • 微机电系统

                • MEMS

                • 中规模数字芯片

                • Medium-Scale Digital Chips

                • 高度集成的数字芯片

                • Highly Integrated Digital Chips

                半导体一词涵盖的范围很广，从奔腾微处理器等知名大芯片到几乎看不见的微型元件。没有一家公司能够制造或销售所有这些不同类型的半导体，也没有工程师、程序员或采购经理能够将它们全部搞清楚。每个人都只专注于半导体的一个小方面。

                The term semiconductor covers a lot of territory, from big famous chips like Pentium microprocessors down to little tiny components that are almost too small to see. No single company makes or sells all these different kinds of semiconductors, and no engineer, programmer, or purchasing manager can keep them all straight. Everyone specializes in just one small aspect of semiconductors.

                就像医学界一样，半导体行业中没有人能够随时掌握甚至完全了解整个行业。医生可能专攻足病学、外科、肿瘤学或儿科。同样，企业经理和工程师可能专攻内存芯片、无线电和电视广播半导体或高压元件。整个行业都有专门针对大型半导体行业中微小而神秘的细分市场的贸易团体和专业会议。市场研究公司会根据外部人士可能不太了解的类别筛选和分类收入和出货量数据。

                Just as with the medical profession, no one in the semiconductor industry can stay current withor even fully understandthe whole industry at once. Doctors might specialize in podiatry, surgery, oncology, or pediatrics. Likewise, business managers and engineers might specialize in memory chips, semiconductors for radio and television broadcasting, or high-voltage components. There are entire trade groups and professional conferences devoted solely to tiny and arcane niches within the larger semiconductor industry. Market research firms sift and sort revenue and shipment data by categories that might make little sense to outsiders.

                为了我们的目的，我们将在本章中将半导体分为几个大类，然后在本章和后面的章节中更详细地探讨一些更有趣的类别。这些划分在业界是公认的；我们并不是武断的。您会发现，在一个主要部门工作的专业人员通常不太了解（或关心）其他部门的半导体是如何工作的、如何销售或谁在使用它们。就像大型医学会议上的医生一样，他们可能能够讨论一些基本的想法，但详细的对话只有同一专业领域的其他人才能理解。

                For our purposes, we'll divide semiconductors into a few big categories in this chapter, and then delve into some of the more interesting ones in more detail, both here and in later chapters. These divisions are well accepted in the industry; we're not being arbitrary. You'll find that professionals working in one major division generally don't understand (or care) very much about how semiconductors in the other divisions work, how they're sold, or who uses them. Like doctors at a large medical convention, they might be able to discuss some basic ideas, but the detailed conversations are intelligible only to others in the same specialized field.

                  半导体家族树

                  Semiconductor Family Tree

                  图 2.1显示了所有类型半导体的总体“家族树”。它从左侧的原始硅（和其他天然材料）开始，逐渐过渡到右侧更复杂的制造半导体类型。沿途的每个框代表您今天可以购买的不同类型的半导体单元或组件。（在本章中，我们使用“组件”一词来指代所有不同类型的半导体产品。稍后，我们将微调我们的术语。）

                  Figure 2.1 shows an overall "family tree" for all types of semiconductors. It starts with raw silicon (and other natural materials) on the left and moves to progressively more elaborate types of manufactured semiconductors on the right. Each box along the way represents a different type of semiconductor unit, or component, that you can buy today. (In this chapter we use the word component to refer to all different types of semiconductor products. Later on, we'll fine-tune our terminology.)

                  图 2.1. 半导体家族树。硅经过加工可制成许多有用的小型、大多为模拟的分立元件。这些元件的组合可制成简单的数字电路，这些电路的组合可形成更大、更复杂的数字电路，例如微处理器。

                  图 2.1也是一种进化图。左侧的组件更原始、更基础，而右侧的组件则更复杂，或者由更简单的组件构建而成。较旧的组件尚未被任何方式替换。它们都活得很好，每年销售数百万或数十亿个单位。（您可以在第 5 章“商业和市场”中看到有关实际销售量和收入的更多详细信息。）根据经验，左侧的组件最便宜，但销量最大。随着向右移动，组件变得更贵，但销量较低。

                  Figure 2.1 is also a kind of evolutionary chart. Components on the left are more primitive and basic, whereas those on the right are more sophisticated or have been built up from the simpler components. The older components haven't been replaced by any means. They're all alive and well and selling millions or billions of units per year. (You can see a lot more detail on the actual sales volumes and revenue in Chapter 5, "Business and Markets.") As a rule of thumb, the components on the left are the cheapest, but sell in the greatest numbers. As you move to the right, the components become more expensive but sell in lower volumes.

                  从小橡子到大橡树

                  From Little Acorns to Great Oak Trees

                  电阻器和电容器等简单电子元件是所有电子产品的基本组成部分。它们由简单的天然材料制成，例如硅、碳或铝。这些简单的元件很小，每个成本仅为几美分，并且为世界各地的客户大量生产。电阻器、电容器或二极管可能和一粒米一样大。

                  Simple electronic components like resistors and capacitors are fundamental building blocks for all electronic products. They're made from simple natural materials, such as silicon, carbon, or aluminum. These simple components are tiny, cost just pennies each, and are manufactured in huge volumes for customers around the world. A resistor, capacitor, or diode might be about as big as a grain of rice.

                  晶体管也是相当基本的元件，但它们在 1947 年被发明时代表了一次重大飞跃。贝尔实验室的两位工程师约翰·巴丁 (John Bardeen) 和沃尔特·布拉顿 (Walter Brattain) 以及他们的老板威廉·肖克利 (William Shockley) 发明了第一个晶体管，为电子技术的进一步发展打开了大门。晶体管成为 20 世纪 50 年代和 60 年代创新浪潮中的关键元件。晶体管帮助定义了“数字”电子技术，最终开启了数字计算机和其他现代便利设备的时代。晶体管还在集成电路 (IC) 的发明中发挥了作用，这代表了半导体制造业的又一次飞跃。

                  Transistors are also pretty elementary components, but they represented a major leap forward when they were invented in 1947. Two Bell Labs engineers, John Bardeen and Walter Brattain, and their boss, William Shockley, invented the first transistor, which opened the doors to further evolution in electronics. Transistors turned out to be the key component in a wave of innovation through the 1950s and 1960s. Transistors helped define "digital" electronics, ultimately ushering in the era of digital computers and other modern conveniences. Transistors also played a role in the invention of integrated circuits (ICs), which represented another leap forward in semiconductor manufacturing.

                  如果将这些基本电子元件（电阻器、电容器、二极管、电感器和晶体管）组合在一起，您几乎可以制造出当今世界上任何电子或计算机控制的设备。这些不起眼的元件是所有现代电子产品的砖瓦。就像砖瓦一样，通常只需以正确的顺序或正确的比例组合它们，就可以决定您创造出什么样的宏伟结构。电气工程师是将这些基本元件组合在一起以制造出奇妙设备的专家。

                  If you combine these basic electronic componentsresistors, capacitors, diodes, inductors, and transistorsyou can create just about any electronic or computer-controlled device in the world today. These humble components are the bricks and mortar of all modern electronics. Like bricks and mortar, it's generally only a matter of combining these in the right order or the correct proportions that determines what grand structure you create. Electrical engineers are experts at combining these basic components to make wondrous devices.

                  图 2.1表明，电阻器、电容器、二极管、电感器和晶体管可以组合起来，形成更复杂的组件，例如逻辑门、转换器和传感器。将这些基本组件混合在一起形成一个更大的组件称为“集成”。这就是集成电路一词的由来。IC 是将一些较简单的组件组合在一起以形成更复杂的组件。典型的 IC 售价可能不到一美元，大小与邮票相当。

                  Figure 2.1 shows that resistors, capacitors, diodes, inductors, and transistors can be combined to create more complex components such as logic gates, converters, and sensors. Mixing these basic components together into one larger component is called "integrating" them. This is where the term integrated circuit comes from. An IC is a mixture of simpler components combined to create a more complex component. A typical IC might sell for less than a dollar and be about the size of a postage stamp.

                  基于这些组件，工程师们制造出了集成度更高的组件。例如，内存芯片、微处理器、可编程逻辑或网络 IC 等复杂而精密的组件，其中包含超过 100 万个基本组件。这些 IC 的售价通常为几美元，体积与火柴盒一样大。

                  Building on these components, engineers create ever more highly integrated components. Some examples are memory chips, microprocessors, programmable logic, or network ICscomplex and sophisticated components that contain more than 1 million basic components within them. These ICs would typically sell for several dollars and be as big as a matchbook.

                  这种不断集成的序列几乎可以永远持续下去。电子工程师不断将前辈创造的组件组合起来，并将更多组件集成到其中。这导致 IC 变得越来越复杂，功能越来越多，功率越来越大。这种不断上升的螺旋式增长为我们带来了内部包含超过 5000 万个组件的组件。例如，用 5000 万个单独的晶体管重新制造奔腾 4 处理器是不可能的，但真正的奔腾 4 处理器却可以装在不及指甲大小的硅片上。

                  This sequence of integration on top of more integration can go on more or less forever. Electrical engineers constantly combine the components their predecessors created and integrate still more components into them. This leads to ever more complex ICs with more features and more power. This continual up ward spiral has given us components that have more than 50 million constituent components inside them. It would be impossible to re-create a Pentium 4 processor, for example, out of 50 million individual transistors, yet the real thing fits on a slice of silicon no bigger than your fingernail.

                  如您所见，组件可以集成以创建新的、更大的组件，依此类推。该过程的每一代都有名称。当四种基本电子元件集成在一起制成 IC 时，有时称为小规模集成 (SSI)。当 SSI 组件进一步集成以创建第二代 IC 时，称为中规模集成 (MSI)。MSI 之后是大规模集成 (LSI)，然后是超大规模集成 (VLSI)。在此之后，术语已经过时，因此 VLSI 现在是一个涵盖任何中等规模芯片的总称。

                  As you can see, components can be integrated to create new, bigger components, and so on. Each generation of this process has been given a name. When the four basic electronic components are integrated to make an IC, it's sometimes called small-scale integration (SSI). When SSI components are integrated still further to create a second-generation IC, it's called medium-scale integration (MSI). After MSI comes large-scale integration (LSI), and then very large-scale integration (VLSI). After this point, the terminology kind of runs out, so VLSI is a now blanket term covering any moderately large chip.

                  集成电路与分立元件

                  Integrated Circuits versus Discrete Components

                  从图 2.1可以看出，并非所有电子元件都是 IC 。任何非集成元件都称为分立元件或独立元件。当人们讨论半导体时，他们通常谈论的是 IC。在普遍的想象中，所有电子元件都是 IC，但实际上只有约 20% 是 IC。其余都是分立元件。

                  Not all electronic components are ICs, as you can see from Figure 2.1. Any nonintegrated component is called a discrete, or separate, component. When people discuss semiconductors it's usually ICs they're talking about. In the popular imagination, all electronic components are ICs, when in reality only about 20 percent are ICs. The rest are discrete components.

                  IC 也被称为芯片。这三个术语是同义词，您可以互换使用。您可能还会听到人们说“计算机芯片”或“微芯片”，但行家们不喜欢这些术语。在本书中，您可以将“芯片”换成“集成电路”或“IC”，没有人会抱怨。

                  ICs are also called chips. All three terms are synonymous and you can use them interchangeably. You might also hear people say "computer chip" or "microchip," but the cognoscenti frown on these terms. Throughout this book you can transpose "chip" with "integrated circuit" or "IC" and no one will complain.

                  分立元件通常非常小，大约只有米粒大小。IC 通常更大，呈矩形，黑色，有银色的小“脚”伸出，如图2.2所示。有些 IC 相当小（这些是第一代 SSI 芯片）。有些 IC 相对较大，例如 5000 万个晶体管的微处理器芯片。如果芯片外观看起来很大，那么可以肯定里面集成了数百万个基本元件。

                  Discrete components tend to be very small, about the size of a grain of rice. ICs are generally bigger, rectangular, and black with small silver "legs" sticking out, as shown in Figure 2.2. Some ICs are fairly small (these are the first-generation SSI chips). Some ICs are comparatively huge, such as a 50-million-transistor microprocessor chip. If a chip looks big on the outside, it's a safe bet there are millions of basic components integrated on the inside.

                  图 2.2。这三种典型的 IC 都包含一个微型硅芯片，该芯片装在黑色塑料封装中，便于操作。十六个金属“脚”允许外部电线连接到内部的实际芯片。图片由 STMicroelectronics, Inc. 提供。经许可使用。

                  杰克·基尔比和罗伯特·诺伊斯是两位独立工作的工程师，两人互不相识，但他们都在 1958 年开发出了第一块集成电路。（诺伊斯获得了专利，而基尔比则在 2000 年获得了诺贝尔奖。）基尔比在 1958 年至 1959 年的圣诞节假期期间从德州仪器公司发明了集成电路。当时在仙童半导体公司工作的罗伯特·诺伊斯也在同一时间使用类似材料开发了类似的芯片。

                  Jack Kilby and Robert Noyce, two engineers working independently and unbeknownst to each other, both developed the first ICs in 1958. (Noyce received the patent for it, but Kilby received a Nobel Prize in 2000.) Kilby created his IC during his 19581959 Christmas break from Texas Instruments. Robert Noyce, then at Fairchild Semiconductor, developed a similar chip using similar materials at the same time.

                  数字与模拟组件

                  Digital versus Analog Components

                  您可能已经从图 2.1中注意到，有些组件被标记为模拟组件，其他组件被称为数字组件，而晶体管似乎兼具两者。这意味着什么？除非您打算从事电子行业，否则意义不大。模拟和数字描述了组件内部的差异以及它如何处理电力。

                  You might have noticed from Figure 2.1 that some of the components are labeled as analog components, others are called digital components, and transistors seem to be a little of both. What does this mean? Not a lot, unless you're planning a career in electronics. Analog and digital describe differences inside the component and how it handles electricity.

                  数字元件将电视为“开”或“关”，没有中间状态。数字元件处理黑与白、真与假、是与否。它们有时也被称为逻辑元件，因为它们将一切都视为整齐划一且合乎逻辑的，没有灰色区域。计算机主要由这些数字或逻辑元件组成。

                  Digital components treat electricity as either on or off, with no in between. Digital components deal in black and white, true and false, and yes and no. They're also sometimes called logic components because they see everything as neat and logical, with no gray areas. Computers are made up mostly of these digital, or logical, components.

                  模拟元件将电流视为稳定流动的流。它们处理的是平滑的灰色变化。模拟元件平滑、塑造和修改通过它们的电流。如果您愿意，您可以将数字元件视为有序、左脑、规则导向的元件，而将模拟元件视为可变的艺术类型。（第 9 章“理论”更详细地解释了数字和模拟元件之间的差异。）图 2.3表示电流如何通过数字和模拟元件。

                  Analog components treat electricity as a steadily flowing stream. They deal in smooth variations of gray, so to speak. Analog components smooth, shape, and modify the electricity passing through them. If you like, you can think of digital components as the ordered, left-brained, rules-oriented components and analog components as the changeable, artistic types. (Chapter 9, "Theory," explains a lot more about the difference between digital and analog components.) Figure 2.3 represents how electricity passes through digital and analog components.

                  图 2.3。逻辑门和内存芯片等数字元件将电流视为开或关，就像电灯开关一样。电阻器和二极管等模拟元件处理不同电平或电压的电流。

                  数字和模拟组件经常会同时用于同一产品，例如电视机。计算机、手机和微波炉也同时包含数字和模拟组件。就像阴和阳或硬件和软件一样，它们是两个完全不同但又相辅相成的东西。

                  Digital and analog components are often used together in the same product, such as televisions. Computers, cell phones, and microwave ovens also include both digital and analog components. Like yin and yang or hardware and software, they are two fundamentally different things that complement each other.

                    简单的模拟元件

                    Simple Analog Components

                    离散模拟元件往往体积较小，因为它们本质上是简单的元件（见图2.4）。在电子技术的早期，所有元件都是简单的模拟元件。自 1960 年左右以来，工程师们一直在将这些离散的构件组合起来，以创建体积更大、更复杂的集成元件。

                    Discrete analog components tend to be physically small because they're fundamentally simple creations (see Figure 2.4). In the early days of electronics, all components were simple analog components. Since about 1960, engineers have been combining these discrete building blocks to create ever more elaborate, integrated components that tend to be physically larger.

                    图 2.4。这些模拟元件分布在两个硅片上，展示了这些元件可以采用的各种形状和尺寸。图片由德州仪器提供。经许可使用。

                    一些模拟元件以小型分立元件的形式出售；其他模拟元件则组合成更大的集成模拟元件，稍后会介绍。设计模拟产品（例如收音机和一些立体声设备）的工程师有时喜欢通过手工挑选每个单独的模拟元件来微调他们的设计。相比之下，设计计算机和其他大型数字产品的工程师则乐于使用 IC，批量购买元件。设计和制造由分立模拟元件组成的复杂产品需要相当多的技巧，而拥有这种天赋的工程师非常稀有且宝贵。

                    Some analog components are sold as small discrete components; others are combined into larger integrated analog components, seen later. Engineers designing analog products (e.g., radios and some stereo gear) sometimes like to fine-tune their designs by hand-picking each individual analog component. In contrast, engineers designing computers and other large digital products are happy to use ICs, taking their components in bulk. There's a fair amount of finesse required to design and build complex products from discrete analog components, and engineers gifted with that talent are rare and valuable.

                    电阻、电容、二极管和其他常见的模拟分立元件比一美分硬币还小，成本更低。这些模拟元件就像半导体世界的昆虫：数量惊人，却几乎被完全忽略。

                    Resistors, capacitors, diodes, and other common analog discrete components are smaller than a penny and cost even less. These analog components are like the insects of the semiconductor world: They are amazingly plentiful and almost totally ignored.

                    有时您可能会听到电子爱好者讨论线性元件，尤其是当他们喜欢短波收音机或高端立体声设备时。线性元件是模拟元件的一个子类。一些模拟元件是线性的，一些是非线性的。线性描述了这些元件如何吸收电能并非常平滑地放大（增加）或衰减（减少）它而不给它添加任何“色彩”。例如，在立体声设备中，重要的是准确地播放音乐，就像它录制的那样，而不添加人为的失真。

                    You might sometimes hear electronics aficionados discussing linear components, especially if they're into short-wave radios or high-end stereo gear. Linear components are a subclass of analog components. Some analog components are linear, and some are nonlinear. Linear describes how these components can take electricity and amplify (increase) or attenuate (decrease) it very smoothly without adding any "coloring" to it. In stereo gear, for example, it's important to play the music exactly as it was recorded without adding artificial distortion.

                    电阻器

                    Resistors

                    让我们从电阻器开始我们的模拟王国之旅，电阻器可能是最简单、最常见的电气元件类型（见图2.5）。电阻器的作用与名称所暗示的差不多：它们阻碍电流通过。电阻器是电子减速带，可释放电压并减缓电流。

                    Let's start our tour of the analog kingdom with resistors, probably the simplest and most common type of electrical component (see Figure 2.5). Resistors do pretty much what their name implies: They resist the passage of electricity. Resistors are electronic speed bumps, bleeding off voltage and slowing the electric flow.

                    图 2.5。电阻器是最简单的电子元件之一。这三个电阻器比铅笔橡皮擦还小，上面的电线比铅笔芯还细。彩色条纹表示每个电阻器提供的电阻量。图片由日立半导体美国公司提供。经许可使用。

                    技术讲座

                    Tech Talk

                    如果您是牛顿第三运动定律和爱因斯坦的 E = mc 2的粉丝，您就会知道能量不能被创造或毁灭，只能被转换。电阻器将其所阻的电能转换为热量；电阻值越大，温度越高。便携式收音机中的微型电阻器产生的热量非常少，甚至无法察觉。但是，一些大电阻器需要金属散热片来防止过热。在极端情况下，电阻器的全部 用途 就是产生热量。汽车后窗除雾器或电炉上的燃烧器都是故意让电阻器发热的例子。

                    If you're a fan of Newton's Third Law of motion and Einstein's E = mc2, you know that energy can't be created or destroyed, only converted. Resistors convert the electricity they're resisting into heat; the bigger the value of the resistor, the warmer it gets. Tiny resistors like those you'd find in a portable radio generate so little heat it's not even noticeable. Some big resistors, though, need metal cooling fins to keep from overheating. In the extreme case, the whole purpose of a resistor is to generate heat. A car's rear-window defogger or burners on an electric range are both examples of resistors that get hot on purpose.



                    虽然降低电流速度似乎毫无意义，但巧妙地组合电阻可以将电压调整到特定的理想水平。从技术上讲，电阻器并不是真正的半导体，因为它们不是由硅制成的。大多数电阻器只是塞入空心管中的碳粉，就像一支小铅笔。大型高压电阻器使用粗线圈代替碳，使它们本质上成为电空间加热器。

                    Although slowing down electric current seems pretty pointless, clever combinations of resistors can adjust voltages to specific and desirable levels. Technically speaking, resistors aren't really semiconductors because they're not made from silicon. Most resistors are just powdered carbon stuffed into a hollow tube, like a tiny pencil. Big, high-voltage resistors use coils of heavy wire in place of the carbon, making them essentially electric space heaters.

                    电阻器非常小，很难在上面印上任何标记，因此它们用彩色带来标识。颜色是电气工程师在职业生涯早期记住的特殊代码。每种颜色代表不同的数字，从 9 到 0：黑色、棕色、红色、橙色、黄色、绿色、蓝色、紫色、灰色和白色。

                    Resistors are so small that it's hard to print any markings on them, so they're identified with colored bands. The colors are a special code that electrical engineers memorize early in their careers. Each color stands for a different number, from nine to zero: black, brown, red, orange, yellow, green, blue, violet, gray, and white.

                    电容器

                    Capacitors

                    第二种最常见的模拟元件是电容器（见图2.6）。同样，这个名字也暗示了它的功能。电容器可以储存少量的电能，就像电动鞋盒一样。电流从电容器的一端流入，并在那里无限期地储存，直到电容器“溢出”。电容器的容量越大，它储存的电量就越多，直到溢出。

                    The next-most common type of analog component is capacitors (see Figure 2.6). Again, the name gives you a hint about its function. Capacitors store small amounts of electricity, like electric shoeboxes. Electricity flows in one end of a capacitor, where it gets stored indefinitely or until the capacitor "overflows." The bigger the capacity of a capacitor, the more electricity it holds until it overflows.

                    图 2.6。电容器只有两根导线，就像电阻器一样。较大的“罐式”电容器包含卷起的箔和塑料层。较小的电容器使用少量绝缘材料来分隔两根导线。图片由日立半导体美国公司提供。经许可使用。

                    电容器只是两个金属板，中间有一个小间隙。电流无法越过这个间隙，所以它会在电容器的一端积聚。最后，当一侧积聚了足够的电流后，所有电流的强大力量会将电流从金属板推向另一侧。最终结果是电流的短暂延迟。如果你习惯修理汽车，你可能还记得更换冷凝器，这只是电容器的另一种说法。冷凝器是一个大电容器，它储存了足够的电能在火花塞中产生火花。

                    Capacitors are simply two metal plates separated by a small gap. Electricity can't jump across this gap, so it builds up at one end of the capacitor. Finally, after enough electricity builds up on one side, the sheer force of all that juice pushes electricity away from the metal plate toward the other side. The net result is a brief time delay in the electric flow. If you're used to repairing cars, you might remember replacing the condenser, which is just another word for capacitor. The condenser is a big capacitor that stores enough electricity to create a spark in the spark plugs.

                    电容器与电阻器一样，从技术上讲不是半导体，因为它们不是由硅制成的。电容器通常包括两块金属板，中间由一块塑料、纸或有时只是空气隔开。为了使电容器小巧紧凑，金属板被卷成像肉桂卷一样的圆柱体。

                    Capacitors, like resistors, aren't technically semiconductors because they aren't made from silicon. Capacitors usually include two metal plates separated by a piece of plastic, paper, or sometimes just air. To make the capacitors small and compact the plates are wound up into a cylinder like cinnamon rolls.

                    电感器

                    Inductors

                    电感器是一种利用磁场来控制电流的特殊元件。它们基本上是由非常细的线圈绕在一个微小的中心芯上。整个电感器可能只有铅笔橡皮擦那么大，但它包含数码长的电线。它们对设计无线电和蜂窝设备的工程师很有用，但电感器在计算机和其他数字产品中并不常见。从外观上看，电感器看起来很像电容器。

                    Inductors are peculiar components that take advantage of magnetic fields to control the flow of electricity. They are basically coils of very fine wire looped around and around a tiny central core. The whole inductor might be only as big as a pencil eraser, but it contains yards and yards of wire. They're useful to engineers designing radio and cellular equipment, but inductors don't show up much in computers and other digital products. From the outside, inductors look much like capacitors.

                    晶体管

                    Transistors

                    晶体管是电阻器、电容器、二极管和电感器进化过程中的重要一步。它们也是我们了解半导体家族树时发现的第一个真正的半导体。（电阻器、电容器和电感器都是电子元件，但它们不是由半导体材料制成的。）1947 年发明的晶体管是半导体物理学的一个里程碑事件。晶体管改变了电子系统的构建方式，为从晶体管收音机到微处理器等各种产品铺平了道路。

                    Transistors are a major step up the evolutionary ladder from resistors, capacitors, diodes, and inductors. They're also the first real semiconductor in our tour of the family tree. (Resistors, capacitors, and inductors are electronic components but they aren't made from semiconducting materials.) The invention of the transistor in 1947 was a landmark event in semiconductor physics. Transistors changed the way electronic systems are built and paved the way for everything from transistor radios to microprocessors.

                    晶体管曾被称为阀门，这相当贴切地描述了它们的功能。晶体管就像水阀或水龙头一样，有电流流入的地方，有电流流出的地方，还有控制电流流的方法。从电气角度来说，晶体管可以调节流动电流的“水压”。它们允许一个电路控制另一个电路，就像控制阀门一样。第 9 章“理论”中将详细介绍晶体管的工作原理。

                    Transistors were once called valves, which is a pretty fair description of what they do. A transistor, like a water valve or a spigot, has a place where current flows in, a place where it flows out, and some way to control the flow. Electrically speaking, transistors adjust the "water pressure" of a flowing electric current. They allow one electrical circuit to control another, like hands on valves. You'll find more discussion of how transistors work in Chapter 9, "Theory."

                    就像水阀一样，晶体管可以调节可变的电流。这使它们成为模拟元件，因为它们可以连续调节电流。同样像阀门一样，晶体管可以完全打开或关闭电流，这使它们成为数字元件。事实上，它们两者兼而有之。晶体管弥补了模拟和数字之间的差距。它们可以像模拟元件一样使用，平稳地调节电流，也可以用作数字元件，充当开/关开关。

                    Like a water valve, transistors can adjust the flow of electricity in variable amounts. This makes them analog components because they adjust electricity in a continuous stream. Also like a valve, transistors can turn the flow on or off completely, which would make them digital components. The fact is, they're both. Transistors bridge the gap between analog and digital. They can be used like analog components, smoothly adjusting electrical flow, or they can be used as digital components, acting as on/off switches.

                    图 2.7显示了有史以来制造的第一个晶体管。电流通过左侧的卷线流入，通过右侧的电线流出。中间的粗线控制电流；它是水龙头上的手。连接到电线上的三角形物体是一块半导体材料。在这种情况下，它不是硅，而是一种称为锗的另一种天然材料。经过一些实验，人们发现硅是一种更好的材料，如今几乎所有的半导体都是由硅制成的。

                    Figure 2.7 shows the first transistor ever made. The electricity flows in through the curly wire on the left and flows out through the wire on the right. The thick wire in the middle controls the flow; it's the hand on the spigot. The triangular object attached to the wires is a chunk of semiconducting material. In this case, it's not silicon but a different natural material called germanium. After some experimentation, silicon was found to be a better material and virtually all semiconductors today are made from silicon.

                    图 2.7。第一个半导体晶体管，由约翰·巴丁 (John Bardeen)、沃尔特·布拉顿 (Walter Brattain) 和威廉·肖克利 (William Shockley) 于 1947 年在贝尔实验室工作时发明。图片由朗讯科技提供。经许可使用。

                    技术讲座

                    Tech Talk

                    摩尔定律是 40 年前半导体行业的一位先驱者提出的一个观点，它出人意料地准确地预测了整个半导体行业的发展速度。

                    Moore's Lawa comment made 40 years ago by one of the industry's early pioneershas turned out to be a surprisingly accurate prediction of how fast the entire semiconductor industry races forward.

                    仙童半导体公司研发主管戈登·摩尔在 1965 年写了一篇文章，推测他的公司和其他电子产品制造商每年可以在硅片上塞入两倍数量的晶体管。十年后的 1975 年，他的预测完全正确。不过，他降低了对未来的预测，预测每次增加一倍需要 18 个月。这后来被非正式地称为摩尔定律，30 年后，他的预测仍然惊人地准确。

                    Fairchild Semiconductor's head of research and development, Gordon Moore, wrote an article in 1965 speculating that his company, and other electronic makers, would be able to squeeze twice as many transistors onto a silicon chip every year. Ten years later, in 1975, his prediction was right on the money. He reduced his estimate going forward, however, forecasting 18 months for each doubling. This became unofficially known as Moore's Law, and after 30 years, his prediction is still uncannily accurate.

                    摩尔定律经常被误传或误解。摩尔定律没有提及计算机速度、微处理器或价格。他的评论仅限于将晶体管封装到硅片上。幸运的是，由于他所预测的持续进步，所有其他好处都已实现。

                    Moore's Law is often misquoted or misunderstood. Moore said nothing about computer speed, microprocessors, or prices. He restricted his comments to packing transistors onto silicon. Happily, all the other benefits have come about because of the continual advances he projected.

                    多年来，包括摩尔本人在内的许多人都曾预测摩尔定律将走向终结，但都未能成功。尽管有许多明智的预言与之相反，但半导体的发展速度仍然令人震惊。

                    Over the years a number of people, including Moore himself, have unsuccessfully predicted the end of Moore's Law. Despite many informed prophecies to the contrary, semiconductor progress continues at an astounding pace.



                    晶体管仍像电阻器和其他分立元件一样单独出售（见图2.8）。然而，更常见的是晶体管组合在一起，通常以数百万个为单位，以形成更大、更复杂的集成元件。

                    Transistors are still sold individually like resistors and other discrete components (see Figure 2.8). It's much more common, however, to see transistors grouped together, often by the millions, to create larger and more elaborate integrated components.

                    图 2.8。晶体管通常有三根导线，尽管有时金属外壳用作第三根导线。电流流入和流出晶体管，流量由第三根导线控制。这些晶体管每个都大约有铅笔橡皮擦那么大。图片由日立半导体美国公司提供。经许可使用。

                    晶体管或多或少取代了收音机和电视机中的真空管。与晶体管一样，真空管也使用电来控制电流。将两者连接在一起，可以制作出复杂的电子电路。真空管的问题是体积大、玻璃容器易碎、耗电量大、发热大。晶体管可以执行所有相同的功能，但不存在上述缺点。除了少数狂热的高保真音响爱好者外，没有人会为真空管的消亡而感到惋惜。

                    Transistors have more or less replaced vacuum tubes in radios and televisions. Like transistors, vacuum tubes used electricity to control the flow of electricity. Linking these together you could make elaborately interrelated electronic circuits. The problems with vacuum tubes were their large size, the frailty of their glass containers, the amount of electricity they used, and the heat they gave off. Transistors perform all the same functions without any of these drawbacks. Except for a few fanatical hi-fi stereo enthusiasts, nobody mourns the passing of vacuum tubes.

                    奇怪的是，晶体管将我们带入了数字电子世界。这很奇怪，因为晶体管就像电阻器或二极管一样是模拟设备。电流以平稳变化的量通过它们，就像水通过逐渐打开的水龙头一样。然而，晶体管能够打开和关闭电流（就像完全关闭水龙头一样）的能力为一种新型电子器件和一种新的思维方式打开了大门。数字电子器件的存在归功于晶体管，以及晶体管在大量使用时可以发挥的许多不同且意想不到的作用。

                    Strangely, transistors lead us into the world of digital electronics. This is strange because transistors are analog devices just like resistors or diodes. Electricity passes through them in smoothly varying amounts, like water through a spigot that's being gradually opened. Yet transistors' ability to turn the electric flow on and offlike shutting off the spigot completelyopened the door to a new kind of electronics and a new way of thinking. Digital electronics owes its existence to transistors and to the many different and unexpected things transistors can do when they're used in large numbers.

                    二极管

                    Diodes

                    二极管为电流提供了单行道。电流只能从一个方向流过二极管，而不能从另一个方向流过。这使得二极管非常适合控制电流，将其引导到需要的地方。从外观上看，二极管看起来很像电阻器，但没有彩色带。

                    Diodes make one-way streets for electricity. Electricity can flow through a diode in one direction but not the other. This makes diodes good for controlling the flow of electricity, directing it to where it's needed. From the outside, diodes look very much like resistors but without the colored bands.

                    发光二极管

                    LEDs

                    有一种特殊的二极管可以发光，因此它显然被称为发光二极管 (LED)，如图 2.9所示。尽管 LED 的工作原理与普通二极管一样，但它们的发光能力比单向电气特性更有趣。当电流试图以“错误”的方向通过 LED 时，它会像普通二极管一样被阻止。但是，当电流以正确的方向通过时，LED 会发光。（对于物理学家来说，电能被转换为可见光。）

                    There's a special kind of diode that gives off light, so it's called, obviously enough, a light-emitting diode (LED), shown in Figure 2.9. Although LEDs work just like normal diodes do, they're more interesting for their lighting ability than for their one-way electrical characteristics. When electricity tries to pass through an LED in the "wrong" direction, it is stopped, just like a normal diode. However, when electricity passes through in the right direction, the LED glows. (For you physicists, the energy of the electricity is converted to visible light.)

                    图 2.9。这组 LED 包括多种颜色的样品。每个都有两根电线和一个塑料透镜。它发出的光的颜色取决于制造 LED 所用的化学物质组合；透镜本身通常是透明的。图片由日立半导体美国公司提供。经许可使用。

                    LED 有几种不同的颜色，但红色是最常见的。大多数家用电子产品，如录像机、微波炉、电视或床头钟，可能都使用红色 LED。它们发出红光只是因为制造 LED 所用的化学物质恰好会发出这种颜色；这不是故意的选择。

                    LEDs come in a few different colors, but red is the most common by far. Most home electronics, like your VCR, microwave oven, television, or bedside clock probably use red LEDs. They glow red simply because the chemicals used to make LEDs happen to give off that color; it was not an intentional choice.

                    技术讲座

                    Tech Talk

                    您可能时不时会看到透明或“白色”LED。这些实际上是特殊的红色LED，带有滤色镜片，可以阻挡红光，就像微型太阳镜一样。滤除此类颜色效率低下，因此透明LED比彩色LED更耗电。

                    You might see clear or "white" LEDs from time to time. These are actually special red LEDs that have a color-filtering lens that blocks the red light, like tiny sunglasses. Filtering out colors like that is inefficient, so clear LEDs waste more electricity than colored LEDs.

                    研究人员长期以来一直在尝试制造蓝色 LED，但直到最近才取得一些成功。为什么比单一颜色更重要？红、绿、蓝 LED 的组合将使制造商能够制造 LED 电视机，而无需使用又大又重又昂贵的玻璃显像管。红、绿、蓝 ( RGB ) 光的组合可以产生眼睛可以看到的任何颜色。没有蓝色，LED电视就不值得一看。

                    Researchers have tried to make blue LEDs for a long time, with little success until recently. Why the big deal over one color? The combination of red, green, and blue LEDs would allow manufacturers to make LED television sets and dispense with big, heavy, expensive glass picture tubes. The combination of red, green, and blue (RGB) lights can create any color the eye can see. Without blue, LED TV wouldn't be worth watching.



                    通过加入不同的化学物质，LED 可以发出不同颜色的光。黄色和绿色 LED 很受欢迎，但蓝色 LED 极其稀有且昂贵。很难找到一种天然物质既能制造出既能发光又能制造出优质二极管。有些红外 LED 发出的颜色是你看不见的。这些 LED 发出红外光谱中的“不可见光”。你的电视遥控器可能使用其中一种。按下遥控器上的按钮；你看到前面有灯闪烁吗？可能没有，因为遥控器中的 LED 发出的光是你眼睛看不见但电视可以看见的颜色。

                    With different chemicals inside, LEDs can be made to glow in different colors. Yellow and green LEDs are popular, but blue LEDs are exceedingly rare and expensive. It's hard to find a natural substance that makes good diodes that can also give off light. There are infrared LEDs that glow in colors you can't see. These LEDs glow in "invisible light" in the infrared spectrum. The remote control for your TV probably uses one of these. Press a button on your remote control; do you see any lights blinking on the front? Probably not, because the LED in your remote emits a color of light your eye can't see but your television can.

                    技术讲座

                    Tech Talk

                    如果您有摄像机或便携式摄像机，请尝试在您操作电视遥控器时录下自己的视频。尽管您看不到遥控器红外LED发出的光，但您的摄像机可能可以。播放录像带，您会看到遥控器向电视闪烁秘密信号。其他遥控器（用于 VCR 等）可能以相同的方式工作。

                    If you have a video camera or camcorder, try videotaping yourself as you operate the remote control for your TV. Even though you can't see the light coming out of the infrared LED in the remote control, your video camera probably can. Play back the tape to see your remote blinking its secret signals to your television. Other remote controls (for your VCR, etc.) probably work the same way.



                    LED 现在用于汽车尾灯、刹车灯和城市交通信号灯，因为它们比灯泡更小、更耐用。一束 LED 中的一两个可能会烧坏，但交通信号灯仍能正常工作。LED 的亮灯速度也比灯泡快。一些眼尖的人报告说，当交通信号灯变红时，它们会“闪烁”，因为 LED 不会像传统灯泡那样发热。

                    LEDs are now being used in car taillights, brake lamps, and city traffic lights because they're smaller and more rugged than light bulbs. One or two LEDs in a cluster can burn out, but the traffic light will still work. LEDs also light up faster than bulbs do. Some sharp-eyed people report seeing traffic signals "flash" when they turn red because LEDs don't warm up the way traditional bulbs do.

                    激光二极管

                    Laser Diodes

                    LED 家族中，最高端的是激光二极管，它们是一种微型激光器，大小不及铅笔橡皮擦。我们都见过激光二极管在商务演示中用作高科技指示器——它们是一种时髦的时尚，但它们在家庭中也很常见。每个立体声 CD 播放器、DVD 电影播放器​​、便携式 CD 播放器、车载 CD 播放器以及计算机中的 CD-ROM 驱动器或 DVD-ROM 都使用激光二极管。大多数家庭视频游戏系统也使用激光二极管。这些小部件推动了消费电子产品和玩具的浪潮。谁会想到，激光，詹姆斯邦德反派的首选武器，会成为无处不在、无害的儿童玩具？

                    At the extreme end of the LED family tree are laser diodes, which are tiny lasers, no bigger than a pencil eraser. We've all seen laser diodes used as high-tech pointers in business presentationsthey're a kind of nerd chicbut they're also common in the home. Every stereo CD player, DVD movie player, portable CD player, in-dash car CD player, and CD-ROM drive or DVD-ROM in a computer uses a laser diode. Most home video game systems use one, too. These little components have enabled a whole wave of consumer electronics and toys. Who would've thought that lasers, the preferred weapon of James Bond villains, would become ubiquitous, harmless children's toys?

                    激光二极管不同于简单的 LED，因为它们发出的是窄光束，而不是向四面八方发光。激光沿直线传播，不会扩散。这就是为什么激光笔会在墙上留下一个小红点，而不是像灯泡那样照亮整个房间。这也是为什么除非直接指向你，否则你看不到激光，而 LED 则从任何地方都可见。制造激光需要精密制造，因此激光二极管比 LED 更贵。激光二极管的紧密光束正是你读取音乐 CD 或 DVD 上雕刻的微小标记所需要的。

                    Laser diodes are different from simple LEDs because they give off a narrow beam of laser light instead of glowing in all directions. Laser light travels in a straight line and doesn't spread out. That's why laser pointers make a small red spot on the wall instead of lighting up the entire room the way a light bulb would. That's also why you can't see a laser unless it's pointed directly at you, as opposed to an LED that's visible from anywhere. Creating a laser requires some precision manufacturing, so laser diodes are more expensive than LEDs. The tight beam of a laser diode is just what you want for reading the tiny marks engraved on a music CD or DVD.

                    光学传感器

                    Optical Sensors

                    光学传感器就像 LED 的反面。它们不发光，而是检测光。它们外观看起来像 LED，但执行相反的任务。您的电视遥控器上有一个 LED，但您的电视前面某处有一个光学传感器，用于检测 LED 发出的光。

                    Optical sensors are like the reverse of LEDs. Instead of giving off light, they detect light. These look like LEDs on the outside put perform the opposite task. Your TV remote control will have an LED on it, but your TV will have an optical sensor somewhere on the front to detect the light given off by the LED.

                    光学传感器无法真正看到或识别图像。它们只能分辨附近的光线是亮还是暗。如果光线闪烁，它们也能分辨出来。电视遥控器的工作原理就是这样的：像隐形版的摩尔斯电码一样，以各种模式闪烁灯光。

                    Optical sensors can't really see or recognize images. They can only tell whether the light nearby is bright or dim. If the light flickers, they can tell that, too. That's how TV remote controls work: by blinking their light off and on in various patterns like an invisible version of Morse code.

                      高级模拟元件

                      Advanced Analog Components

                      数字元件并不是唯一集成到大型 IC 中的元件。模拟元件也以有趣的方式组合在一起。有些元件，如电荷耦合器件 (CCD) 阵列，一旦集成，就会开辟新的市场和产品。其他元件，如微机电传感器 (MEMS)，乍一看似乎很奇怪。

                      Digital components aren't the only ones that are integrated into larger ICs. Analog components, too, have been combined in interesting ways. Some, like charge-coupled device (CCD) arrays, open up new kinds of markets and products once they're integrated. Others, like micro-electrical mechanical sensors (MEMS), seem just plain weird at first glance.

                      CCD 图像传感器

                      CCD Image Sensors

                      CCD 图像传感器是数码相机和其他有趣的图像识别产品的基础。CCD 图像传感器是一种芯片，其单个光传感器排列成方形图案或阵列，就像浴室地板上的瓷砖一样。图像传感器可能有 100 个“瓷砖”，上下各 100 个，也可能每个方向都有数千个。此平铺阵列中的每个单个传感器都可以感应一个光点或像素。它们一起可以“看到”整个图像。阵列中的传感器越多，图像就越清晰，这就是为什么你会听到相机专家吹嘘 20 万像素的相机比 3 万像素的相机更好。

                      CCD image sensors form the basis of digital cameras and other interesting image-recognition products. A CCD image sensor is a chip with individual light sensors arranged in a square pattern, or array, like tiles on a bathroom floor. The image sensor might have 100 "tiles" across and 100 up and down, or it might have thousands in each direction. Each individual sensor in this tiled array can sense one dot, or pixel, of light. Together, they can "see" an entire image. The more sensors in the array, the sharper and clearer the image will be, which is why you'll hear camera experts bragging about how that 20-megapixel camera is better than a 3-megapixel camera.

                      还有其他类型的图像传感器，例如 CMOS 图像传感器，但它们的工作原理基本相同。数千或数百万个单独的光传感器以方形图案排列在芯片上，以产生一幅大而清晰的图像。

                      There are other types of images sensors, such as CMOS image sensors, but they all work in basically the same way. Thousands or millions of individual light sensors are arranged in a square pattern on a chip to produce one large, clear image.

                      其他传感器

                      Other Sensors

                      传感器还包括温度传感器、压力传感器、加速度传感器、磁传感器等等。温度传感器本质上是电子温度计，可用于家用恒温器以及许多工业用途。它们的工作原理是利用某些材料在变热（或变冷）时的行为方式。有些材料在热或冷时导电性更好。工程师们已经发现了它们的属性究竟发生了多大的变化，并且可以通过测量芯片的导电量来确定芯片的温度。

                      Also under the heading of sensors are temperature sensors, pressure sensors, acceleration sensors, magnetic sensors, and many more. Temperature sensors are essentially electronic thermometers, useful for household thermostats as well as many industrial uses. They work by taking advantage of the way some materials behave when they get hot (or cold). Some materials conduct electricity better when they're warm or when they're cool. Engineers have discovered exactly how much their properties change and can determine the temperature of the chip by measuring how much electricity it conducts.

                      磁传感器的工作原理与此类似。有些材料在磁场中的表现不同，因此围绕这些材料构建的芯片可以检测出磁性的细微差异。这在电子罗盘（检测地球磁场）中很有用，甚至可以通过检测磁性的细微差异来测量大块钢材中的缺陷。

                      Magnetic sensors work in somewhat the same way. Some materials behave differently in the presence of magnetic fields, so chips built around these materials can detect slight differences in magnetism. This is useful in electronic compasses (detecting the Earth's magnetic field) or even for measuring flaws in bulk steel by sensing slight differences in its magnetic properties.

                      化学实验室和医学实验室使用小型传感器来检测某些气味或气体。与温度传感器一样，某些材料在暴露于某些气体时会表现出不同的行为。工程师们测量了这些差异，并制造出在氧气等气体存在下发出电脉冲的芯片。就像煤矿中的金丝雀一样，这些化学传感器芯片可以比实验室技术人员更早地检测到极少量的气体或毒药。

                      Chemistry labs and medical labs use small sensors that detect certain smells or gases. Like the temperature sensors, some materials behave differently when they're exposed to certain gases. Engineers have measured these differences and created chips that give off tell-tale electrical impulses in the presence of, say, oxygen. Like a canary in a coal mine, these chemical sensor chips can detect very minute amounts of gas or poison before laboratory technicians can.

                        A/D 和 D/A 转换器

                        A/D and D/A Converters

                        转换器连接着模拟和数字电子世界。有模拟到数字转换器（通常称为 A/D 转换器，或简称为 ADC）和数字到模拟转换器（称为 D/A 转换器，或 DAC）。这些组件看似不起眼，但实际上却很常见。每个 CD 播放器、MP3 播放器和便携式音乐播放器都至少有一个 D/A 转换器，用于将数字数据流转换为耳机或扬声器的模拟信号。有些播放器会有两个或更多个 DAC，每个扬声器一个。任何“无带”数字电话应答机都将包括一个 A/D 转换器，用于记录您的问候语并将其转换为数字数据，然后将其存储在内存芯片中。您可能听到的任何合成声音都来自 D/A 转换器。

                        Converters bridge the world of analog and digital electronics. There are analog-to-digital converters (usually called A/D converters, or just ADCs) and digital-to-analog converters (called D/A converters, or DACs) that go the other way. Obscure as these components might seem, they're actually quite common. Every CD player, MP3 player, and portable music player has at least one D/A converter to convert the digital data stream into an analog signal for the headphones or speakers. Some will have two or more DACs, one for each speaker. Any "tapeless" digital telephone answering machine will include an A/D converter that records your greeting and converts it into digital data before storing it in memory chips. Any synthesized voices you might hear emanate from D/A converters.

                          微机电系统

                          MEMS

                          MEMS 确实是最奇怪的半导体类型。即使是业内人士也不太了解 MEMS，它拥有一批忠实的追随者，但名声却非常混乱。MEMS 既不是数字的也不是模拟的，甚至并不总是半导体。它们可能由硅制成，但并不总是以任何有用的方式导电。MEMS 基本上是微型机械设备，只是碰巧使用芯片制造技术制造而成。

                          MEMS are truly the strangest type of semiconductor. Little understood even by industry insiders, MEMS have a devoted following and a greatly confused reputation. Neither digital nor analog, MEMS aren't even always semiconductors. They might be made of silicon but they don't always conduct electricity in any useful way. MEMS are basically tiny mechanical devices that just happen to be built using chip-manufacturing techniques.

                          MEMS 一词与内存无关。它是微机电传感器的缩写，这是一种对其工作原理的笨拙技术描述。MEMS 使用微型齿轮和杠杆来移动物体或感知微观尺度上的运动。MEMS 可以嗅探化学物质、分离血细胞或测量加速度——所有这些功能都需要机械运动而不仅仅是电流。MEMS 是使用硅加工设备制造的，这使得它们非常小巧且相对便宜（见图2.10）。

                          The term MEMS has nothing to do with memory. It's short for micro-electrical mechanical sensor, an awkwardly technical description of how they function. MEMS use tiny gears and levers to move things or sense motion on a microscopic scale. MEMS can sniff chemicals, separate blood cells, or measure accelerationall functions that require mechanical movement and not just electrical current. The fact that MEMS are built using silicon-processing equipment allows them to be incredibly small and relatively inexpensive (see Figure 2.10).

                          图 2.10。这个微型齿轮和链条传动装置实际上是用电子显微镜拍摄的硅片。齿轮比蚂蚁的头还小，链条上每个环节的大小与大细菌相当。由于 MEMS 的惯性很小，因此整个组件运行速度非常快。

                          安全气囊可能是 MEMS 最流行的用途。这些微型传感器的硅表面蚀刻有微型机械杠杆。如果芯片受到足够大的撞击（例如在严重的汽车事故中），杠杆会稍微弯曲。如果杠杆弯曲得足够大，就会形成一个电路，用于点燃炸药并使安全气囊充气。这些微型加速度计非常可靠、非常小巧、非常便宜，而且易于大批量生产，非常适合汽车行业的大规模生产。

                          Airbags are probably the most popular use of MEMS. These tiny sensors have microscopic mechanical levers etched into their silicon surface. The lever bends ever so slightly if the chip is knocked hard enough, as in a serious automobile accident. If the lever bends enough it completes an electrical circuit that isused to ignite an explosive charge and inflate the airbag. These miniature accelerometers are very reliable, very small, very inexpensive, and easy to manufacture in high volume, making them a perfect fit for auto industry mass production.

                            中规模数字芯片

                            Medium-Scale Digital Chips

                            工程师们发现晶体管可以用作电力的开关后，一个全新的数字电子领域就诞生了。数字元件的工作原理是将电力视为摩尔斯电码。数字元件不是用点和划来控制电码，而是控制微量的电力的开和关。接收这些传输的其他数字元件可以对其进行解码，就像电报员接收电报一样。一串数字元件一起工作可以创建一长串复杂的功能，因为每个环节都会将其功能添加到其他环节的功能中。有了足够多的这些环节，你就可以创造出看似智能的电子设备，比如电脑。

                            Once engineers discovered that transistors could be used as on/off switches for electricity, a whole new field of digital electronics was born. Digital components work by treating electricity as if it were Morse code. Instead of dots and dashes, digital components switch tiny amounts of electricity on and off. Other digital components receiving these transmissions can decode them, like a telegraph operator receiving a telegram. A string of digital components working together can create long chains of elaborate functions as each link adds its ability to that of the others. With enough of these links you can create seemingly intelligent electronic devices, such as computers.

                            某些晶体管组合非常有用，可以将它们预先封装到第一批数字集成电路中。这些集成电路又产生了集成度更高的集成电路，以此类推。数字芯片的复杂程度从每芯片几百个晶体管到每芯片数千万个晶体管不等，中间经历了许多步骤。

                            Certain combinations of transistors were useful enough to prepackage them into the first digital ICs. These, in turn, led to more highly integrated ICs, and so on. Digital chips span the scale of complexity from a few hundred transistors per chip to tens of millions of transistors per chip, with many steps along the way.

                            逻辑门

                            Logic Gates

                            逻辑门是数字电子技术的起点。它们比晶体管高出一个层次，是数字时钟、视频游戏、个人电脑和上百万种其他产品的基本构件。逻辑门由几个晶体管以及可能几个电阻器或电容器组成。一般来说，一个逻辑门相当于大约六个晶体管。

                            Logic gates are the starting point for digital electronics. They're one level up the evolutionary ladder from transistors and the fundamental building blocks for digital clocks, video games, personal computers, and a million other products. A logic gate consists of a few transistors, plus perhaps a few resistors or capacitors. As a general rule of thumb, one logic gate is equivalent to about six transistors.

                            门之所以如此命名，是因为它们控制着电流的流动。牲畜栅栏门控制着牛的流动；逻辑门控制着数字电子脉冲。逻辑门并不智能，但它们是合乎逻辑的。它们根据非常简单的输入做出非常简单的决定。例如，有一种逻辑门称为反相器。它只是将其输入传递到其输出，但方向相反。在摩尔斯电码中，这就像将所有点转换为划线，将所有划线转换为点。这并不是特别困难，但它对某些电子功能很有用。

                            Gates are so named because they gate, or control, the flow of electricity. Barnyard gates control the flow of cattle; logic gates control pulses of digital electronics. Logic gates aren't smart but they are logical. They make very simple decisions based on very simple inputs. For example, one type of logic gate is called an inverter. It simply passes its input to its output, but reversed. In Morse code, this would be like converting all the dots to dashes and all the dashes to dots. This is not spectacularly challenging, but it is useful for certain electronic functions.

                            其他类型的逻辑门包括或门（即单词“或”，而不是字母“或”）；与门和异或门。这些门衍生出 NAND（负与）门、NOR（负或）门和 XNOR（异或负或）门等变体。缓冲器、反相器和名字奇怪的触发器构成了逻辑门的“流氓画廊”。如果您想了解有关逻辑门及其功能的更多信息，请将其视为邀请，直接跳至第 9 章“理论”。

                            Other types of logic gates are OR gates (that's the word "or," not the letters O-R); AND gates, and exclusive-OR gates. From these come variations such as the NAND (negative-AND) gate, the NOR (negative-OR) gate, and XNOR (exclusive-negative-OR) gate. Buffers, inverters, and the curiously named flip-flop round out the rogues' gallery of logic gates. If you'd like to know more about logic gates and what they do, take this as an invitation to skip ahead to Chapter 9, "Theory."

                            技术讲座

                            Tech Talk

                            数学中有一整支专门研究或、与、或非和其他逻辑函数的数学分支。布尔代数以英国数学家乔治布尔的名字命名，是所有计算机和数字逻辑芯片的基础。问任何计算机程序员或工程师，他们都会告诉你，布尔逻辑是他们必须学习的第一件事。

                            There's a whole branch of mathematics devoted to the OR, AND, NOR, and other logic functions. Named after English mathematician George Boole, Boolean algebra underpins all computers and digital logic chips. Ask any computer programmer or engineer and they'll tell you that Boolean logic was the first thing they had to learn.

                            后来，克劳德·香农、约翰·文恩（维恩图的提出者）和查尔斯·道奇森（一位英国执事兼兼职数学家，还以刘易斯·卡罗尔为笔名创作了儿童读物）对布尔的工作进行了进一步的阐释。

                            Boole's work was later enhanced by Claude Shannon, John Venn (he of the Venn diagram), and Charles Dodgson, an English deacon and part-time mathematician who also wrote children's books under the name Lewis Carroll.



                            逻辑门简单又小巧，因此不单独出售。你可以花几便士购买包含 AND、OR、XOR 或 NAND 门的小芯片（见图2.11）。业余爱好者和学生经常使用这些小芯片来构建简单的电子项目。

                            Logic gates are simple and small so they're not sold individually. You can buy small chips with collections of AND, OR, XOR, or NAND gates in them for a few pennies (see Figure 2.11). Hobbyists and students often use these small chips to build simple electronic projects.

                            图 2.11。这种典型的 IC 包含一些简单的逻辑门。该芯片总共有 14 个引脚，可能包含大约四个独立的逻辑功能，外加两个电源引脚。电子工程师和业余爱好者可以使用这些类型的芯片构建大型项目。图片由日立半导体美国公司提供。经许可使用。

                              高度集成的数字芯片

                              Highly Integrated Digital Chips

                              一旦将晶体管和其他分立元件集成到更大的集成元件中，这种趋势就一发不可收拾。如今，大芯片包含数百万个逻辑门，这意味着数百万个晶体管、电阻器、二极管、电容器和其他基本元件都集成在一起。

                              Once the trend toward integrating transistors and other discrete components into larger integrated components was under way, there was no stopping it. Today, big chips contain millions of gates of logic, which implies millions of transistors, resistors, diodes, capacitors, and other basic components all rolled together.

                              这种高度集成的芯片通常被称为 VLSI 元件。没有专门的测试来判断芯片是否为 VLSI 设备；晶体管数量超过一百万的芯片可能就符合 VLSI 要求。按照这个标准，大多数新芯片都符合 VLSI 元件的条件。

                              Such highly integrated chips are generically called VLSI components. There's no specific test for a chip to be considered a VLSI device; anything more than about a million transistors probably qualifies. By that measure, most new chips qualify as VLSI components.

                              这些大型数字芯片有多种形式，从内存芯片到微处理器芯片。这些是有史以来最复杂、最精致的半导体元件，它们的盈利能力反映了它们的进步。顶级微处理器芯片的售价可超过 1,000 美元。它们采用最先进的硅制造技术，需要工程师团队花费多年时间进行设计和开发。

                              These large-scale digital chips take many forms, from memory chips to microprocessor chips. These are the most complex and elaborate semiconductor components ever created, and their profitability reflects their advancements. Top-of-the-line microprocessor chips can sell for more than $1,000 each. They use the most advanced silicon manufacturing technology and take teams of engineers many years to design and develop.

                              内存芯片

                              Memory Chips

                              内存芯片是数量最多的一种大型数字芯片，因为很多产品都使用内存芯片。您的 PC 中可能至少有 8 个内存芯片，但也可能有 64 个或更多。微波炉、CD 播放器、闹钟以及您能想到的几乎所有其他电子设备中可能都至少有一个内存芯片。

                              Memory chips are the most plentiful kind of large-scale digital chips because so many products use so many of them. Your PC probably has at least eight memory chips inside, but it could have 64 or more. Microwave ovens, CD players, alarm clocks, and nearly any other electronic device you can think of, probably all have at least one memory chip inside them.

                              全球半导体制造商每年生产约 100 亿块内存芯片。内存芯片虽然复杂，但几乎可以算作商品，价格极具竞争力，销量巨大。电子市场上的内存芯片价格每天都在波动，分析师们像追踪珍贵的股票投资组合一样追踪内存价格。多年来，内存生产逐渐从美国转移到日本，然后转移到韩国、台湾和新加坡。由于内存芯片对价格非常敏感，因此其生产往往会转移到能够制造它们的最廉价劳动力资源。

                              The world's semiconductor makers produce about 10 billion memory chips every year. As complex as they are, memory chips are nearly commodities, priced very aggressively and sold in enormous volumes. Prices for memory chips fluctuate daily in electronics markets, and analysts track memory prices like treasured stock portfolios. Over the years, memory production gradually moved from the United States to Japan, and then to Korea, Taiwan, and Singapore. Because memory chips are so price sensitive, their production tends to shift to the cheapest labor pool able to manufacture them.

                              内存芯片有什么用处？显然，它们可以记忆或存储电子信息。这并不像听起来那么可怕或复杂。内存芯片基本上是微型电容器阵列，这些简单的模拟元件用于存储电能。由于电容器非常小，排列非常紧密，因此内存芯片可以同时容纳数百万个独立电荷。

                              What do memory chips do? Obviously, they remember, or store, electrical information. That's not as eerie or as complicated as it sounds. Memory chips are basically arrays of tiny capacitors, those simple analog components for storing electricity. Because the capacitors are very small and arranged in very tight rows, memory chips can hold millions of separate electrical charges at once.

                              内存芯片有许多不同的子类型，第 7 章“内存基本指南”将介绍这些子类型。该章还详细介绍了内存芯片的工作原理。两种主要的内存分类是 RAM 和 ROM。RAM 芯片可以擦除并重复使用以存储不同的数据，而 ROM 芯片是永久性的，可以永久保存数据。

                              Memory chips come in many different subtypes, which are covered in Chapter 7, "Essential Guide to Memory." That chapter also explains more about how memory chips work. The two major memory classifications are RAM and ROM. RAM chips can be erased and reused to store different data, whereas ROM chips are permanent, holding data forever.

                              通信芯片

                              Communications Chips

                              通信芯片负责处理计算机、卫星和建筑物之间的数据通信。它们曾经只是简单的“比特泵”，本身不具备智能；它们只是在计算机的控制下将数据喷射到电线上。现在，通信芯片本身已经变得像微处理器一样，具有在传输数据之前格式化、缓冲和处理数据或在接收数据时解包数据的智能。随着世界对即时通信的需求不断增长，最新一代的通信芯片已经迎接了这一挑战。

                              Communications chips handle data communications between computers, satellites, and buildings. They were once simple "bit pumps" that had no intelligence of their own; they just squirted data down a wire under the control of a computer. Now communications chips have become like microprocessors in their own right, with the intelligence to format, buffer, and massage data before it's transmitted or unpacking data as it's received. As the world's desire for instant communication has increased, the newest generations of communications chips have risen to the challenge.

                              您可以在电线杆顶部和蜂窝基站天线“树”上找到专用通信芯片。它们会即时压缩和解压缩语音对话，将我们的声音转换成密集的（有时是加密的）数据包，然后通过铜线或光纤发送。在回程中，这些相同的芯片会解压缩（和解密）我们朋友的声音并将其重新组合成音频形式。随着这些通信芯片变得越来越先进，电话公司能够在同一根电线或光纤上同时进行越来越多的对话。

                              You'll find specialized communications chips atop telephone poles and in cellular base station antenna "trees." They compress and decompress voice conversations on the fly, converting our voices into densely packed (and sometimes encrypted) data packets before sending them down copper wire or optical fiber. On the return trip, these same chips decompress (and decrypt) our friends' voices and reconstitute them into audio form. As these communications chips get more advanced, telephone companies are able to squeeze more and more simultaneous conversations onto the same wires or fibers.

                              随着互联网和网络的兴起，通信芯片市场也开始腾飞。如今，通过互联网传输的数据量如此之大，以至于在传输过程中的几个步骤中都需要智能和专用的芯片来确保您的电子邮件到达正确的位置。一些芯片执行一种互联网分类，将高优先级数据流量（例如流视频广播）与低优先级数据流量（例如电子邮件垃圾邮件）分开。其他芯片用于安全保护，在信用卡号通过网络时对其进行加密和解密。通信芯片的清单几乎无穷无尽，制造它们的业务瞬息万变且发展迅速。

                              With the rise of the Internet and the Web, the market for communications chips has taken off. So much data is now transferred through the Internet that intelligent and specialized chips are required at several steps along the way to make sure your e-mail gets to the right place. Some chips perform a sort of Internet triage, separating the high-priority data traffic (e.g., a streaming video broadcast) from the low-priority ones (e.g., e-mail spam). Other chips are used for security, encrypting and decrypting credit card numbers as they pass through the network. The list of communications chips is almost endless and the business of creating them is volatile and fast moving.

                              图形芯片

                              Graphics Chips

                              自 20 世纪 90 年代以来，图形和 3D 芯片已迅速成为 PC 组件业务的重要组成部分。随着 PC 越来越多地用于游戏、DVD 视频和其他类似电视的任务，图形芯片的重要性也随之上升。最新的图形芯片非常复杂和强大，使用数百万个晶体管，在性能和复杂度方面可与一些微处理器相媲美。在许多真人电脑游戏中，3D 图形芯片比 PC 中的微处理器工作得更辛苦。狂热的 PC 游戏玩家苦苦思索要购买哪种 3D 图形芯片，并认真阅读每篇产品评论。

                              Graphics and 3D chips have surged to become a major part of the PC components business since the 1990s. As PCs are used more and more for games, DVD video, and other television-like tasks, the importance of graphics chips has risen. The latest graphics chips are amazingly complex and powerful, using millions of transistors and rivaling some microprocessors for performance and intricacy. In many live-action computer games, the 3D graphics chip works harder than the microprocessor in the PC. Avid PC gamers agonize over what 3D graphics chip to buy and diligently read every product review that comes out.

                              除了个人电脑，图形芯片还用于 DVD 播放器等家用电子产品。高端计算机系统使用图形芯片来呈现复杂的信息，用于天气预报、飞机设计、应力分析、喷气模拟或核、化学和医学研究。

                              Apart from PCs, graphics chips are used in home electronics, such as DVD players. High-end computer systems use graphics chips to render complex information for weather forecasting; aircraft design; stress analysis; jet simulation; or nuclear, chemical, and medical research.

                              多年来，图形芯片的性能和功能已大幅提升。早期的图形芯片只不过是一个 D/A 转换器和一些内存。计算机将数据放入内存，然后 D/A 转换器将其转换为屏幕的模拟电信号。现在，3D 图形芯片可以与其所服务的微处理器相媲美。它们根据数学模型渲染 3D 图像，生成数百万种颜色，根据光源和强度计算折射角，将重叠的物体隐藏在彼此后面，并将远处的物体淡入背景。创建 3D 场景所涉及的数学运算复杂而晦涩，而每秒 60 次实现所有这些操作的电路令人印象深刻。这是大量致力于娱乐的技术。

                              The performance and capabilities of graphics chips have risen dramatically over the years. Early graphics chips were little more than a D/A converter and some memory. The computer put data into the memory and the D/A converter turned it into an analog electrical signal for the screen. Now 3D graphics chips rival the microprocessor they're serving. They render 3D images from mathematical models, generate millions of colors, calculate angles of refraction based on light sources and intensities, hide overlapping objects behind one another, and fade distant objects into the background. The mathematics involved in creating 3D scenes is complex and arcane, and the circuitry involved in making all this happen 60 times per second is impressive. It's a lot of technology all devoted to entertainment.

                              外设

                              Peripherals

                              外围芯片之所以得名，是因为它们用于计算机的外部边缘或外围。外围芯片是计算机的守门人或海关代理，负责将传入数据引导到其所属的位置，并发送传出数据。

                              Peripheral chips are so named because they are used around the outside edges, or periphery, of computers. Peripheral chips are the gatekeepers or customs agents of a computer, channeling incoming data where it belongs and sending outgoing data on its way.

                              外围芯片控制打印机、键盘、扬声器、鼠标、操纵杆或您可能插入计算机的任何其他设备。每个外围芯片专门用于一种类型的插件，因此一台装备精良的计算机将包含几种不同的外围芯片。除了计算机之外，外围芯片还用于工业和科学系统，或任何有计算机连接到现实世界外部的东西的地方。

                              Peripheral chips control printers, keyboards, speakers, mice, joysticks, or anything else you might plug into your computer. Each peripheral chip specializes in one type of plug-in, so a well-equipped computer will include several different peripheral chips. In addition to computers, peripheral chips are also used in industrial and scientific systems, or anywhere there's a computer connected to something outside in the real world.

                              随着人们发明新的计算机使用方法，外设芯片的数量和类型也随之发生变化。键盘芯片问世已久，但控制操纵杆的芯片问世较晚。几年前，两种新的 PC 连接通用串行总线 (USB) 和 FireWire 芯片进入市场。虽然外设芯片相当复杂，但它们也相当便宜。计算机制造商认为它们与商品无异，因此它们的价格往往较低，使用寿命较短。

                              The number and type of peripheral chips change over time as people invent new ways to use computers. Keyboard chips have been available for a long time, but chips for controlling joysticks came later. A few years ago, chips for universal serial bus (USB) and FireWire, two new PC connections, entered the market. Although peripheral chips are fairly complicated, they're also pretty inexpensive. They're considered little better than commodities by computer makers, so their prices tend to be low and their life spans short.

                              定制芯片：ASIC 和 ASSP

                              Custom Chips: ASICs and ASSPs

                              大多数大型半导体公司的大型工程师团队负责设计大型芯片。芯片设计是一项艰巨的工作，成本也很高。然而，在过去 10 年左右的时间里，芯片设计的壁垒逐渐瓦解。设计芯片仍然绝非易事，但它已不再是过去那种神秘的黑魔法。现在，一家中型公司考虑设计自己的芯片已成为可能。

                              Big teams of engineers working at huge semiconductor companies design most large-scale chips. Chip design is difficult work, and the costs are high. However, over the past 10 years or so, the barriers to chip design have crumbled, little by little. Designing a chip is still not easy by any means, but it's not the mysterious black art it once was. It's now within the realm of possibility for a medium-sized company to consider designing its very own chip.

                              为什么你会想要定制芯片？也许没有一家大型芯片制造公司能生产出你想要的芯片。也许你想要一个具有特定容量的内存芯片，或者一个以特定方式传输数据的通信芯片，或者一个使用特殊密码或代码系统加密信息的安全芯片。制造定制芯片的原因和考虑它的公司一样多。

                              Why would you want to? Well, maybe none of the major chip-making companies produce just the chip you're looking for. Maybe you want a memory chip with a certain capacity, or a communications chip that transmits data a certain way, or a security chip that encrypts information using your special password or code system. There are as many reasons for making a custom chip as there are companies considering it.

                              这些定制芯片的术语是专用集成电路 (ASIC)。ASIC 是任何定制设计的芯片的统称，与由主要芯片公司批量生产的芯片不同。您不必将定制的 ASIC 卖给任何人。事实上，这通常是关键所在。ASIC 为制造它的公司提供了竞争优势；它是电视、微波炉或防抱死制动系统内的秘密武器。

                              The term for these custom chips is application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC). An ASIC is a general term for any chip that is custom designed, as opposed to a chip that's mass-produced by one of the major chip companies. You don't have to sell your custom ASIC to anyone. In fact, that's usually the point. An ASIC gives a competitive advantage to the company that makes it; it's a secret weapon inside the television, microwave oven, or antilock brake system.

                              “特定应用”是什么意思？“应用”这个词在这个意义上意味着产品。这是另一个不幸的例子，一个常见的英语单词被技术界滥用了。特定应用意味着芯片是为某些特定类型的产品设计的，比如电梯或汽笛。这也意味着芯片在特定市场之外用处不大。

                              What does "application-specific" mean? The word application in this sense means product. It's another unfortunate case of a common English word that's been perverted somewhat by the technical community.
