Application-specific means the chip is intended for some particular type of product, like elevators or steam whistles. It also implies the chip isn't very useful outside of that specific market.

                              ASIC 本质上是定制的，因此每个 ASIC 都不同。ASIC 可以大或小，复杂或（相对）简单。它可能包括本章开头附近的家族树中的任意组件组合。ASIC 内部可能有一个或多个微处理器、一些内存、一些模拟组件、一些可编程逻辑或几乎任何其他东西。

                              ASICs by their nature are custom, so every one is different. An ASIC can be big or small, complex or (relatively) simple. It might include any combination of components from the family tree near the beginning of this chapter. An ASIC might have one or more microprocessors inside, some memory, some analog components, some programmable logic, or nearly anything else.

                              设计和制造 ASIC 并不便宜，因此公司不会轻易承担这项任务。在第一块芯片准备好之前，工程时间、材料和服务的成本很容易就高达 100 万美元。公司希望得到一些保证，确保他们的 ASIC 的好处大于开发的风险和成本。首先，这意味着 ASIC 只适用于大批量产品，如数码相机、手机、汽车等。

                              Designing and building an ASIC isn't cheap, so companies don't undertake the task lightly. It can easily cost $1 million in engineering time, materials, and services before the first chip is ready. Companies want some guarantee that the benefits of their ASIC will outweigh the risks and costs of its development. For starters, that means ASICs are created only for high-volume products like digital cameras, cell phones, automobiles, and so forth.

                              当 ASIC 是为销售而非内部使用而设计时，它被称为专用标准产品 (ASSP)。“标准产品”部分意味着该芯片可供任何想要购买的人使用，这是一种非定制芯片。ASIC 和 ASSP 之间没有任何技术差异；区别纯粹是经济上的。

                              When an ASIC is designed for sale, as opposed to internal use, it's called an application-specific standard product (ASSP). The "standard product" part implies that the chip is available to anyone who wants to buy it, a sort of noncustom custom chip. There's no technical difference at all between an ASIC and an ASSP; the distinction is purely economic.

                              除了 ASIC 和 ASSP，定制芯片有时也被称为片上系统 (SoC)。这个术语没有任何特定含义；它用于模糊地描述一种特别大或复杂的 ASIC，其中包括最终产品所需的一切，全部包含在一个芯片中。第8 章“定制和可配置芯片基本指南”更详细地介绍了 ASIC、ASSP 和 SoC 的世界。

                              In addition to ASIC and ASSP, custom chips are sometimes called a system-on-a-chip (SoC). This term doesn't have any specific meaning; it's used to vaguely describe a particularly large or complex ASIC that includes everything the final product will need, all in a single chip. The world of ASICs, ASSPs, and SoCs is mapped out in more detail in Chapter 8, "Essential Guide to Custom and Configurable Chips."

                              可编程逻辑芯片

                              Programmable Logic Chips

                              许多公司都想开发自己的 ASIC，但没有足够的勇气或资金。对于他们来说，有一种折衷方案，即一种半定制芯片。这些芯片被称为可编程逻辑器件 (PLD)。不同的 PLD 公司使用不同的术语，因此您还会听到它们被称为复杂可编程逻辑器件 (CPLD) 和现场可编程门阵列 (FPGA)。这些和其他类型的定制芯片将在第 8 章“定制和可配置芯片基本指南”中介绍。

                              Many companies would like to develop their own ASIC but don't have the stomachor the deep pocketsfor it. For them, there is a middle ground, a kind of semicustom chip. These chips are called programmable logic devices (PLDs). Different PLD companies use different terminology, so you'll also hear them called complex programmable logic devices (CPLDs) and field-programmable gate array (FPGA). These and other types of custom chips are covered in Chapter 8, "Essential Guide to Custom and Configurable Chips."

                              可编程逻辑芯片就像电子版 Etch-a-Sketch，可以直接使用但尚未真正完成。客户将自己的设计印在芯片上，制作自己的半定制芯片。定制可编程逻辑芯片远不如从头设计和构建“真正的”ASIC 芯片那么困难。就像 Etch-a-Sketch 一样，您可以随时擦除芯片并重新开始，因此没有任何风险。

                              Programmable logic chips are like electronic Etch-a-Sketches, ready to use but not really finished. Customers imprint their own design onto them, making their own semicustom chips. Customizing a programmable logic chip is nowhere near as difficult as designing and building a "real" ASIC chip from scratch. Like an Etch-a-Sketch, you can erase the chip and start over any time you want, so there's no risk.

                              可编程逻辑芯片外观与普通芯片无异，但内部却是“空白的”。它们让设计师和工程师有机会用理论芯片设计来玩“假设”游戏。在一个下午的时间里，您可以在同一个可编程逻辑芯片上创建和测试六种不同的芯片设计。PLD 为工程师提供了一块发挥创造力的空白画布，而且也是一块可清洗的画布，因为单个可编程逻辑芯片可以反复使用。当设计最终完成后，芯片可以永久安装到产品中，在那里它将像任何其他芯片一样运行。

                              Programmable logic chips look like normal chips on the outside but they're "blank" on the inside. They give designers and engineers a chance to play "what if" with theoretical chip designs. In the space of an afternoon, you can create and test half a dozen different chip designs on the same programmable logic chip. PLDs provide a blank canvas for engineers to be creative, and a washable one, too, because a single programmable logic chip can be used over and over. When the design is finally complete, the chip can be permanently installed into a product, where it will operate like any other chip.

                              这种灵活性也有缺点。首先，可编程逻辑芯片比其他芯片慢。完全相同的芯片设计在 PLD 中的运行速度要比在以正常方式制造的 ASIC 中慢。可编程逻辑芯片也比 ASIC 更昂贵。预计要出货成千上万个芯片的公司会因为 PLD 的单价较高而避免使用 PLD。从好的方面来看，PLD 不需要数百万美元的开发成本。因此，尽管 PLD 一开始肯定更便宜，但从长远来看，它们可能会更昂贵。

                              There are downsides to all this flexibility. For one, programmable logic chips are slower than other chips. The exact same chip design will run slower in a PLD than it would in an ASIC manufactured by the normal means. Programmable logic chips are also more expensive than their ASIC counterparts. Companies that expect to ship thousands and thousands of chips shy away from using PLDs because of their higher unit price. On the plus side, there's no million-dollar development cost for a PLD. So although PLDs are definitely cheaper in the beginning, they might be more expensive in the long run.

                              微处理器

                              Microprocessors

                              微处理器是半导体发展的巅峰，至少微处理器制造商会这样告诉你。它们是大众媒体所钟爱的“芯片上的计算机”。不可否认的是，微处理器是所有半导体中最复杂、最精密的，它们已经彻底改变了我们的经济、社会和科学世界。

                              Microprocessors are the pinnacle of semiconductor development, or at least that's what the microprocessor makers will tell you. They are the "computer on a chip" so beloved by the popular press. There's no denying that microprocessors are the most complex and elaborate of all semiconductors or that they've forever altered our economic, social, and scientific worlds.

                              微处理器使随时随地的廉价计算成为可能。计算机曾经是政府拥有的大型、嘈杂的机器，由身着白大褂的科学家团队维护。现在它们出现在每个现代家庭、汽车和电话中，无处不在，几乎看不见。计算机可能比其运行所需的电池更便宜。所有这些都发生在人类一代人的时间内。

                              Microprocessors have enabled cheap, anywhere, anytime computing. Computers used to be large, noisy machines owned by governments and tended by teams of scientists in white lab coats. Now they're in every modern home, car, and telephone, ubiquitous to the point of invisibility. Computers can be cheaper than the batteries they run on. All of this has happened in the span of one human generation.

                              第一个微处理器发明于 1971 年；现在每几个月就能卖出 10 亿个。令人惊讶的是，这些微处理器芯片几乎没有一个用于计算机。大多数人将微处理器等同于 PC，但这远非全部。计算机只是微处理器芯片用途的一小部分。微处理器在完全不相关的家庭、娱乐、安全和工业用途方面的影响远远超出了任何人的预测。芯片上的计算机实际上与计算机几乎没有任何关系。

                              The first microprocessor was invented in 1971; now 1 billion are sold every few months. Surprisingly, almost none of those microprocessor chips are used in computers. Most people equate microprocessors with PCs but that's far from the whole picture. Computers are just a tiny fraction of what microprocessor chips are used for. Microprocessors have made a far greater impact in totally unrelated household, entertainment, security, and industrial uses than anyone could have predicted. The computer on a chip actually has very little to do with computers anymore.

                              微处理器表现出惊人的适应能力。就像微型机器人一样，它们可以被命令（编程）完成从普通到复杂的各种任务。微处理器不再用于预测天气或计算导弹轨迹，而是更常用于烹饪食物、打开炉子、打开车库门、播放音乐或炸毁想象中的外星人。普通家庭拥有大约二十多个微处理器，甚至还不包括家用电脑。普通汽车还配备了十几个微处理器，有些汽车甚至配备了 60 多个微处理器。几乎所有插在墙上或使用电池的东西都可能装有微处理器芯片。

                              Microprocessors have shown themselves to be amazingly adaptable. Like tiny robots, they can be commanded (programmed) to do any number of chores from the mundane to the complex. Instead of predicting the weather or calculating missile trajectories, microprocessors are used more commonly to cook food, turn on the furnace, open garage doors, play music, or blast imaginary space aliens. The average household has about two dozen microprocessors or more, without even counting home computers. The average car includes another dozen microprocessors; some have more than 60. Nearly anything that plugs into the wall or uses batteries is likely to have a microprocessor chip in it.

                              微处理器的形状和大小各有不同，并非所有微处理器都是我们在电视广告中看到的那种大而快的芯片。事实上，很少有微处理器芯片的价格超过 5 美元。绝大多数微处理器芯片都藏在日常家用电器和玩具中。微处理器制造商已经开始专业化，因此有些芯片适用于家用电器，有些适用于汽车，有些适用于视频游戏，等等。每种芯片都有自己的名称或缩写。

                              Microprocessors come in all shapes and sizes, and not all of them are the big, fast chips we see advertised on television. In fact, few microprocessor chips cost more than $5. The overwhelming majority of microprocessor chips are squirreled away inside everyday household appliances and toys. Microprocessor makers have started to specialize, so some chips are good for home appliances, some are for automobiles, some are for video games, and so on. Each variation has its own name or abbreviation.

                              微处理器有多种类型，它们都有三个字母的缩写，如 CPU、MPU、MCU、DSP 或 NPU。现在我们将它们视为相同，并将它们称为微处理器。有关更多详细信息，请参阅第 6 章“微处理器基本指南”，了解这些芯片的用途。

                              There are different types of microprocessors, and they all have three-letter abbreviations like CPU, MPU, MCU, DSP, or NPU. For now we'll treat them all the same and just call them microprocessors. For more in-depth information, turn to Chapter 6, "Essential Guide to Microprocessors," to see what these chips are all about.

                                第 3 章 芯片是如何设计的

                                Chapter 3. How Chips Are Designed

                                在本章中...

                                In this chapter...

                                • 旧式设计流程

                                • Old-Style Design Process

                                • 新型设计流程

                                • New-Style Design Process

                                • 验证设计是否有效

                                • Verifying the Design Works

                                • 使用外部 IP

                                • Using Outside IP

                                • 开始录制和拍摄

                                • Getting to Tape Out and Film

                                • 当前问题和未来趋势

                                • Current Problems and Future Trends

                                自从第一批半导体芯片被手工组装以来，芯片设计已经取得了长足的进步。很少有一个行业能如此频繁、如此彻底地自我改造。如今的新芯片设计方式与 10 年前完全不同；几乎可以肯定，再过 10 年，该职位的描述将再次发生变化。

                                Chip design has come a long way since the first semiconductor chips were assembled, literally, by hand. Rarely does a profession reinvent itself so often and so fundamentally. New chips today are designed in a completely different manner from those of just 10 years ago; it's almost certain that the job description will change again in another 10 years.

                                新芯片的设计自然是在计算机的帮助下进行的。这些计算机（通常称为工程工作站）及其内部的芯片本身就是以这种方式设计的，为整个过程提供了一个很好的闭环。芯片设计工程师使用的计算机与普通 PC 没有根本区别，甚至专用软件对于普通 PC 用户来说也不会显得太陌生。

                                New chips are designed, naturally enough, with the help of computers. These computers (often called engineering workstations) and the chips inside them were themselves designed this way, providing a nice circular closure to the entire process. The computers that chip-design engineers use are not fundamentally different from a normal PC, and even the specialized software would not look too alien to a casual PC user.

                                然而，这种软件价格高得惊人，而且它本身就支撑着一个价值数十亿美元的产业。电子设计自动化 (EDA) 是一种创建和销售芯片设计软件的业务，它为全球成千上万的计算机程序员提供支持。芯片设计工程师依赖他们的计算机和 EDA 软件“工具”，就像木匠依赖一套专用工具一样。有少数几家大型 EDA 供应商，尤其是 Synopsys（加利福尼亚州山景城）、Mentor Graphics（俄勒冈州波特兰）和 Cadence Design Systems（加利福尼亚州圣何塞），它们相当于 Craftsman、Stanley 和 Black & Decker。还有许多规模较小的“精品” EDA 供应商，它们为利基市场的芯片设计师提供专用软件工具。

                                That software is breathtakingly expensive, however, and supports a multibillion-dollar industry all by itself. Called electronic design automation (EDA), the business of creating and selling chip-design software supports thousands of computer programmers around the world. Chip-design engineers rely on their computers and their EDA software "tools" the way a carpenter relies on a collection of specialized tools. There are a handful of large EDA vendors, notably Synopsys (Mountain View, California), Mentor Graphics (Portland, Oregon), and Cadence Design Systems (San Jose, California) that are the equivalent of Craftsman, Stanley, and Black & Decker. There are also numerous smaller "boutique" EDA vendors that supply special-purpose software tools to chip designers in niche markets.

                                无论芯片设计师使用什么工具，他们的目标始终是相同的：为新芯片创建工作蓝图并使其做好制造准备。在芯片设计领域，这被称为“制作胶片”，因为胶片是芯片设计师的最终目标。芯片制造商在工厂中使用胶片（我们将会看到，它实际上不再是胶片）来实际制造芯片，这一过程将在下一章中描述。

                                Regardless of the tools a chip designer uses, the goal is always the same: to create a working blueprint for a new chip and get it ready for manufacturing. In the chip-design world, that's called "getting to film," as film is the ultimate goal of a chip designer. The film (which is really not film any more, as we shall see) is used by chip makers in their factories to actually manufacture the chip, a process that's described in the next chapter.

                                  旧式设计流程

                                  Old-Style Design Process

                                  在个人电脑、EDA 和自动化工具出现之前，工程师最初使用的是红宝石，这是一种由美术用品商店出售的红色塑料薄膜，至今仍被标牌制作者和平面设计师使用。早期的芯片设计师会用 X-acto 刀将红宝石切成条状，然后将它们粘贴到挂在墙上的大型透明板上。最终芯片中的每一层硅或铝都需要单独的薄片，上面覆盖着用胶带粘贴的十字交叉条纹图案。

                                  Before personal computers, EDA, and automated tools, engineers originally used rubylith, a red plastic film sold by art-supply houses that is still used today by sign makers and graphic artists. Early chip designers would cut strips of rubylith with X-acto knives and tape them to large transparent sheets hanging on their wall. Each layer of silicon or aluminum in the final chip required its own separate sheet, covered with a criss-crossing pattern of taped-on stripes.

                                  通过将两张或更多张透明薄片叠放在一起并仔细对齐，您可以检查以确保一张薄片上的红宝石与另一张薄片上的红宝石在正确的位置接触。或者，您可以确保胶带条不会接触，从而在实际芯片中造成不必要的电气短路。这当然是一项艰苦的工作，但这正是先驱者所经历的磨难。整个过程有点像设计一座高楼，在一张单独的纸上画出每一层楼，然后堆叠这些纸以确保墙壁、电线、楼梯和管道都精确匹配。

                                  By laying two or more of these transparent sheets atop one another and lining them up carefully, you could check to make sure that the rubylith from one touched the rubylith from another at exactly the right points. Or, you'd make sure the tape strips didn't touch, creating an unwanted electrical short in the actual chip. This was painstaking work, to be sure, but such are the tribulations of the pioneers. The whole process was a bit like designing a tall building by drawing each floor on a separate sheet and stacking the sheets to be sure the walls, wiring, stairs, and plumbing all match up precisely.

                                  这项任务被称为流片，原因显而易见。流片是（现在仍然是）每个芯片设计项目中的一个重要里程碑。一旦流片，就几乎完成了。所有初步设计工作都已完成，所有计算都经过反复检查，所有规划也已完成。剩下要做的就是等待芯片制造出来。

                                  This task was called taping out, for reasons that are fairly obvious. Tape out was (and still is) a big milestone in every chip-design project. Once you'd taped out, you were nearly done. All the preliminary design work was complete, all the calculations were checked and double-checked, and all the planning was finished. About the only thing left to do was to wait for the chip to be made.

                                  不过，在兴奋地等待硅之前，还有最后一步。你必须用超大的红宝石层制作胶片。这是一个简单的摄影缩减过程。每个覆盖红宝石的层都用作掩模，将交叉阴影投射到小胶片底片上。它的工作原理就像幻灯机在大屏幕上显示度假快照，但缩减过程不是让图像变大，而是让图像变小。每个单独的红宝石层都投射到不同的胶片底片上，该底片的尺寸与芯片本身完全相同，边长不到一英寸。现在你有了一套可以送去制作的胶片。

                                  One last step remained, however, before you could get excited about waiting for silicon. You had to make film from your oversized rubylith layers. This was a simple photographic reduction process. Each rubylith-covered layer was used as a mask, projecting criss-crossed shadows onto a small film negative. It works just like a slide projector showing vacation snapshots on a big screen, but instead of making the images bigger, the reduction process makes them smaller. Each separate rubylith layer is projected onto a different film negative that is exactly the size of the chip itself, less than one inch on a side. Now you have a film set that you can send for fabrication.

                                    新型设计流程

                                    New-Style Design Process

                                    如今，这个过程已经完全不同了，尽管它同样艰辛和复杂。现代芯片设计工具已经消除了容易出错的手工贴合各层的工作，但它们只是转移了工作量。现代数百万晶体管芯片提供的新挑战足以弥补这一差异。

                                    Today the process is radically different, although no less painstaking or complex. Modern chip-design tools have done away with the error-prone manual work of taping up individual layers, but they only shift the workload. Modern multimillion-transistor chips supply more than enough new challenges to make up the difference.

                                    EDA 设计工具

                                    EDA Design Tools

                                    现代芯片太过复杂，无法手动设计。没有哪位工程师能够亲自了解新芯片内部发生的一切。即使是工程师团队，也没有哪位成员真正了解设计的所有细节和细微差别。一个人可能管理项目并指挥芯片的整体架构，但个别工程师将负责详细设计的部分内容。他们必须作为一个团队一起工作，他们必须相互依赖和信任，以及他们的工具。

                                    Modern chips are far too complex to design manually. No single engineer can personally understand everything that goes on inside a new chip. Even teams of engineers have no single member who truly understands all the details and nuances of the design. One person might manage the project and command the overall architecture of the chip, but individual engineers will be responsible for portions of the detailed design. They must work together as a team, and they must rely on and trust each other as well as their tools.

                                    这些工具都是计算机程序。就像经验丰富的木匠会收集满满一箱他喜欢的工具一样，芯片设计师也会开发一系列计算机程序，帮助芯片设计的各个方面。没有一种 EDA 工具能够从头到尾完成芯片设计，就像没有一种木匠工具可以完成所有工作一样。工具的种类很重要，使用多种 EDA 工具是工程师技艺的一部分。

                                    Those tools are all computer programs. Just as an experienced carpenter will accumulate a toolbox full of favored tools, chip designers develop a repertoire of computer programs that aid in various aspects of chip design. No single EDA tool can take a chip design from start to finish, just as no carpenter's tool can do every job. The assortment is important, and using a mixture of EDA tools is part of an engineer's craft.

                                    原理图捕获

                                    Schematic Capture

                                    示意图是用于表示电路的传统方式。至少对于简单的电路来说确实如此。示意图或接线图就像地铁地图。它们或多或少真实地绘制了电线和组件（线路和车站）的实际排列。为了便于理解，示意图可能会稍微风格化一些，就像伦敦地铁的经典路线图一样，但在大多数情况下，示意图是准确的，是电路连接的地图，如图3.1所示。

                                    Schematic diagrams are the time-honored way of representing electrical circuits. At least that's true for simple electrical circuits. Schematics, or wiring diagrams, are like subway maps. They draw, more or less realistically, the actual arrangement of wires and components (lines and stations). The diagram might be stylized a bit for easier understanding, like the classic route map for the London Underground, but for the most part, schematics are accurate, maps of circuit connections, as shown in Figure 3.1.

                                    图 3.1。此典型原理图显示了两个 IC（中心附近的矩形）如何通过导线（直线）连接到其他组件。电阻器、电容器、二极管、LED 和其他组件均用标准符号表示。除了 IC 之外，原理图上的图形看起来与电路中的实际组件并不一样。

                                    如果工程师的最终目标是将设计转移到胶片上以制作芯片，那么在纸上绘制原理图对工程师没有任何好处。相反，原理图是使用原理图捕获软件在计算机屏幕上绘制的。有了它，您可以将各种电气元件（加法器、电阻器等）的符号拖放到屏幕上，然后通过在它们之间画线将它们连接起来。原理图捕获软件可以处理更简单的注释工作，例如标记每个功能并确保没有电线悬在半空中。原理图捕获软件有点像文字处理软件，它不会提供灵感或才华，也不会从无到有地创造设计，但它可以捕捉常见错误并使您的工作空间免受令人尴尬的擦除痕迹。

                                    Drawing a schematic on paper doesn't do an engineer any good if the goal is to ultimately transfer that design into film to have a chip made. Instead, schematics are drawn on a computer screen using schematic-capture software. With this, you can drag and drop symbols for various electrical components (adders, resistors, etc.) across your screen and then connect them by drawing wires between them. The schematic-capture software takes care of the simpler annotation chores like labeling each function and making sure no wires are left dangling in midair. Schematic-capture software is a bit like word-processing software in that it won't provide inspiration or talent or create designs from nothing, but it will catch common mistakes and keep your workspace free from embarrassing erasure marks.

                                    许多公司提供原理图捕获软件，但大多数供应商都是小公司，而且他们的队伍正在缩小。现代芯片太复杂了，无法以这种方式设计，不是因为原理图捕获程序无法处理，而是因为工程师无法处理。使用原理图捕获软件设计数百万晶体管的芯片就像用小画笔和调色板画一座桥。要覆盖的区域太多了，时间不够。

                                    A number of companies supply schematic-capture software, but most vendors are small firms and their ranks are dwindling. Modern chips are too complex to be designed this way, not because the schematic-capture programs can't handle it, but because the engineers can't. Designing a multimillion-transistor chip using schematic-capture software would be like painting a bridge with a tiny artist's brush and palette. There's just far too much area to cover and not enough time.

                                    硬件综合

                                    Hardware Synthesis

                                    为了减轻一点一点设计芯片的乏味，工程师们开始采用一种称为硬件综合的新方法。综合并不像听起来那么现代：芯片不是凭空合成的。相反，工程师们向计算机输入有关芯片组织的指令，然后计算机生成详细的电路设计。（具体方法将在下一节中介绍。）工程师仍然需要设计芯片，只是不必设计得如此详细。这就像一砖一瓦一寸一寸地描述一堵砖墙与告诉助手“给我建一堵三英尺高、十英尺长的砖墙”之间的区别。如果你有一个值得信赖的、擅长砌砖的助手，无论哪种方式，你都应该得到相同的结果。

                                    To alleviate some of the tedium of designing a chip bit by bit, engineers have turned to a new method, called hardware synthesis. Synthesis is not quite as space-age as it might sound: Chips are not magically synthesized from thin air. Instead, engineers feed their computers instructions about the chip's organization and the computer generates the detailed circuit designs. (The exact method for doing this is described in the next section.) The engineer still has to design the chip, just not at such a detailed level. It's like the difference between describing a brick wall, brick by brick and inch by inch, or telling an assistant, "Build me a brick wall that's three feet high by 10 feet long." If you have an assistant you trust who is skilled in bricklaying, you should get the same result either way.

                                    从理论上讲，硬件综合也是如此，但实际情况却有所不同。尽管当今的芯片设计师已在工作中大量采用硬件综合，但他们仍对这种权衡有所抱怨。例如，综合设计的运行速度往往比“手工制作”的芯片设计慢 20% 到 30%。合成芯片的运行速度可能不是 500 MHz，而是 400 MHz。如果是低成本芯片，实际上只需要以 250 MHz 的速度运行，那么这还算可以。但是，如果您销售的是用于个人电脑的高端微处理器，那就麻烦了。因此，仍有几种芯片没有使用硬件综合进行设计，因为供应商无法承受性能下降的后果。

                                    Theoretically, that's true of hardware synthesis as well, but the reality is somewhat different. Although today's chip designers have overwhelmingly adopted hardware synthesis for their work, they still grumble about the trade-offs. For example, synthesized designs tend to run about 20 to 30 percent slower than "handcrafted" chip designs. Instead of running at 500 MHz, a synthesized chip might run at only 400 MHz. That's fine if it's a low-cost chip that really only needs to run at, say, 250 MHz. However, it's a showstopper if you're selling prestigious high-end microprocessors for personal computers. There are a few types of chips, therefore, that are still not designed using hardware synthesis because the vendor can't afford the reduction in performance.

                                    硬件合成的另一个缺点是，最终的芯片在硅片面积方面通常要大 30% 到 50%。硅片越多意味着成本越高，这既因为它们需要更多的原材料，也因为圆形硅片上能容纳的芯片越少。芯片越大意味着制造良率越低。同样，有些芯片制造商不使用硬件合成，因为他们要尽可能地节省每一分钱的成本。

                                    Another drawback of hardware synthesis is that the resulting chips are often about 30 to 50 percent larger in terms of silicon real estate. More silicon means more cost, both because they need more raw material and because fewer chips fit on a round silicon wafer. Bigger chips mean lower manufacturing yields. Once again, there are certain chip makers that don't use hardware synthesis because they're shaving every penny of cost possible.

                                    第三，合成设计芯片比手工设计的芯片耗电量更大。这是前面提到的硅片尺寸更大的副作用。硅片越多，耗电量就越多，差异可能达到 20% 甚至更多。对于极低功耗的芯片（例如手机中使用的芯片），手工芯片仍然很受欢迎。

                                    Third, chips made from synthesized designs tend to use more electricity than do manually designed chips. That's a side effect of the larger silicon size previously mentioned. More silicon means more power drained, and the difference can be 20 percent or more. For extremely low-power chips, such as the ones used in cellular telephones, handcrafted chips are still popular.

                                    尽管存在这些严重的缺陷，但大多数新芯片都是通过综合设计创建的，因为没有其他办法。即使是大型工程团队也需要硬件综合程序的帮助才能在合理的时间内完成大型芯片。如果你手工砌每一块砖，那么完成一座大教堂需要很长时间。

                                    Despite all these serious drawbacks, most new chips are created from synthesized designs simply because there's no other way. Even big engineering teams need the help of hardware-synthesis programs to finish a large chip in a reasonable amount of time. It takes a long time to finish a cathedral if you're laying every brick by hand.

                                    公司通常会同时使用综合和手工制作两种设计风格。新芯片的第一代通常采用硬件综合语言（后面会介绍）进行设计，以便尽快推出并投放市场。芯片发布后（假设销售情况良好），公司可能会命令工程师修改或重新设计芯片，这次使用更耗费人力的方法来缩小硅片尺寸、降低功耗并降低制造成本。芯片的“第二次旋转”通常会在第一版发布六到九个月后出现。当微处理器制造商宣布现有芯片的更快、升级版本时，新芯片通常就是这样制造的。

                                    Companies will often use both design styles, synthesis and handcrafting. The first generation of a new chip will usually be designed with hardware-synthesis languages (described later) to get the chip out the door and onto the market as quickly as possible. After the chip is released (assuming that it sells well), the company might order its engineers to revise or redesign the chip, this time using more labor-intensive methods to shrink the silicon size, reduce power consumption, and cut manufacturing costs. This "second spin" of the chip will often appear six to nine months after the first version. When microprocessor makers announce faster, upgraded versions of an existing chip, this is often how the new chip was created.

                                    硬件描述语言

                                    Hardware-Description Languages

                                    在一定程度上，原理图是不错的，但对于现代芯片所采用的大规模设计来说，它们过于注重细节。相反，工程团队需要更高级、更抽象的东西；让他们能够大胆思考，避免陷入他们所创造的众多电气细节中。他们想要的是某种方式来描述他们想要的东西，并让工具神奇地将其实现。

                                    Schematics are fine, up to a point, but they're too detail-oriented for large-scale designs, which modern chips have become. Instead, engineering teams need something that's more high-level and more abstract; something that allows them to think big and avoid getting bogged down in so many of the electrical details of what they're creating. What they'd like is some way to describe what they want, and have a tool magically produce it.

                                    进入硬件描述语言 (HDL)，这是从原理图捕获程序进化而来的下一步。HDL 还支持硬件综合。使用 HDL，工程团队可以设计电路的行为，而无需详细设计电路本身。HDL 工具将把工程师的愿望（尽管是非常具体和精心定义的愿望）转化为电路设计。HDL 用户无需使用原理图捕获软件来绘制加法器及其所有相关接线，只需指定他或她希望将两个数字相加即可。HDL 工具处理选择加法器和接线的具体工作。

                                    Enter hardware-description languages (HDLs), the next step up the evolutionary ladder from schematic-capture programs. HDLs also enable hardware synthesis. Using an HDL, engineering teams can design the behavior of a circuit without exactly designing the circuit itself in detail. The HDL tool will translate the engineers' wishes (albeit very specific and carefully defined wishes) into a circuit design. Instead of using schematic-capture software to draw an adder and all of its attendant wiring, an HDL user can simply specify that he or she wants two numbers added together. The HDL tool handles the detail work of selecting an adder and wiring it up.

                                    HDL 远非神奇。与所有计算机程序一样，它们非常拘泥于字面意思，可能会误解用户的意愿。工程师花费数年时间学习如何有效使用 HDL，并且必须非常有条不紊地定义他们想要什么。芯片设计越大，失败的可能性就越大，因此确保一切正确的压力就越大。

                                    HDLs are far from magical. Like all computer programs, they're very literal minded and can misinterpret their user's wishes. Engineers spend years learning to use HDLs effectively and have to be very methodical about defining what they want. The bigger the chip design, the greater the opportunity for failure, so the greater the pressure to make sure everything's right.

                                    HDL 看起来与原理图捕获完全不同。使用 HDL 不像在屏幕上画图，更像是写作。毕竟，它是一种硬件描述语言。工程师使用 HDL 以分步程序的形式告诉计算机他们想要什么样的电路。然后，计算机解释这些步骤并生成等效电路图。如果原理图是蓝图，那么 HDL 就是配方。

                                    HDLs look nothing like schematic capture. Instead of drawing figures on a screen, using an HDL is more like writing. It's a hardware-description language, after all. Engineers use an HDL to tell their computer what kind of circuit they want, in the form of a step-by-step procedure. The computer then interprets the steps and produces an equivalent circuit diagram. If schematics are blueprints, HDLs are recipes.

                                    对于大型芯片来说，这个程序描述可能长达数十万行，和一本小说一样长。图 3.2显示了 HDL 代码的一个示例。它必须准确描述芯片在任何情况下所做的一切。

                                    For a large chip, this procedural description can be hundreds of thousands of lines long, as long as a novel. A sample of HDL code is shown in Figure 3.2. It has to describe absolutely everything the chip does under all circumstances.

                                    如果您熟悉计算机编程和软件，您可能已经认识到 HDL 的概念；它们是编程语言。矛盾的是，HDL 是一种解决硬件问题的软件方法——它们是一种“编写”新硬件的方法。

                                    If you're familiar with computer programming and software, you've probably already recognized the concept of HDLs; they're programming languages. Paradoxically, HDLs are a software approach to a hardware problemthey're a way to "write" new hardware.

                                    图 3.2 HDL 代码摘录描述了加法器电路的工作原理。HDL 编译器将这一详细描述转换为原理图，然后交给工程师进行构建，或者更有可能与其他 HDL 组件组合以制作更大的芯片。
