                                                                                                  4,294,967,296

                                                                                                  4,294,967,296

                                                                                                  64

                                                                                                  64

                                                                                                  18,446,744,073,709,551,616

                                                                                                  18,446,744,073,709,551,616

                                                                                                  有些处理器还可以“分割位”。如果 16 位处理器不需要计算 65,536 这样的大数字，那么它可能能够同时进行两次 8 位计算，只要两次计算都不会产生大于 256 的答案。这种双重方法允许芯片在相同的时间内完成两倍的工作。对于 32 位处理器，尤其是 64 位处理器，这实际上非常常见。即使是您附近​​的核物理学家也几乎不需要 64 位算法。宇宙中的原子数量并不多。当今的 64 位微处理器更常用于同时进行四次 16 位计算（或八次 8 位计算，或两次 32 位计算）。

                                                                                                  Some processors can also "split their bits." If a 16-bit processor doesn't need to calculate numbers as big as 65,536 it might be able to do two 8-bit calculations at once, as long as neither one generates an answer bigger than 256. This double-barreled approach allows the chip to do twice as much work in the same amount of time. For 32-bit processors, and especially 64-bit processors, this is actually very common. Even your neighborhood nuclear physicist hardly ever needs 64-bit arithmetic. There just aren't that many atoms in the universe. Today's 64-bit microprocessors are more often used for doing four 16-bit calculations (or eight 8-bit calculations, or two 32-bit calculations) at once.

                                                                                                  技术讲座

                                                                                                  Tech Talk

                                                                                                  如果您对数学感兴趣，您可能已经注意到表 6.1中的模式。右边的数字是 2 的左边数字的幂。因此，4 位处理器可以处理最多 2 4 的值，即 16；2 8等于 256；等等。其原因在第 9 章“理论”中详细说明，但这与计算机使用二进制或以 2 为基数的算术有关。

                                                                                                  If you're mathematically inclined, you might have noticed the pattern in Table 6.1. The number on the right is 2 raised to the power of the number on the left. So, a 4-bit processor can handle values up to 24, which is 16; 28 equals 256; and so on. The reasons for this are detailed in Chapter 9, "Theory," but it has to do with the fact that computers use binary, or base 2, arithmetic.

                                                                                                    性能、基准和千兆赫

                                                                                                    Performance, Benchmarks, and Gigahertz

                                                                                                    据说计算机世界里有谎言、该死的谎言和基准。就像马克·吐温最初对统计数据的观察一样，数字并不能说明全部情况，甚至连一半都不能说明。测量微处理器芯片的速度似乎是一项简单、直接的任务，但事实并非如此。

                                                                                                    It's said in the computer world that there are lies, damn lies, and benchmarks. Like Mark Twain's original observation about statistics, the numbers don't tell the whole story, or even the half of it. Measuring the speed of a microprocessor chip might seem to be a simple, straightforward task, but it's anything but.

                                                                                                    举个例子，试想一下世界上最好的汽车。你会测量最高速度吗？后备箱空间？燃油效率？价格？转售价值？你可以把所有这些因素结合起来，并进行加权，但其他人肯定会认为你太重视速度，而对乘客舒适度重视不够。你不可能用一个分数取悦所有人。这就是测量微处理器芯片（和计算机）的问题。每个人都希望看到一个微处理器“优点”的单一分数，但没有人同意应该测量什么。

                                                                                                    As an example of the problem, try defining the world's best car. Do you measure top speed? Trunk space? Fuel efficiency? Price? Resale value? You could combine and weight all these factors, but other people will inevitably argue that you've given too much importance to speed and not enough to passenger comfort, for example. You can't please everyone with a single score. This is the problem with measuring microprocessor chips (and computers). Everyone would like to see a single score for microprocessor "goodness," but nobody agrees on what that should measure.

                                                                                                    技术讲座

                                                                                                    Tech Talk

                                                                                                    兆赫、千兆赫及更高频率

                                                                                                    Megahertz, Gigahertz, and Beyond

                                                                                                    微处理器（或任何类型的数字芯片）的速度通常以赫兹为单位。1 赫兹表示“每秒变化一次”。如果您每秒抛一枚硬币，则该硬币的变化率为 1 赫兹。如果您能以某种方式每秒完成 1,000 次该技巧，那么您抛硬币的频率就是 1,000 赫兹，即 1 千赫兹 (KHz)。1 百万赫兹为 1 兆赫兹 (MHz)，10 亿赫兹为 1 千兆赫兹 (GHz)。

                                                                                                    The speed of microprocessors (or any type of digital chip) is often measured in hertz. One hertz means one "change per second." If you flip a coin every second, that coin is changing at the rate of 1 hertz. If you can somehow do that trick 1,000 times per second you'd be flipping a coin at 1,000 hertz, or 1 kilohertz(KHz). One million hertz is a megahertz (MHz) and 1 billion hertz is a gigahertz (GHz).

                                                                                                    廉价的微处理器可能运行在 20 MHz 左右；而更昂贵的 PC 处理器运行在 1 GHz 以上。该测量单位以德国科学家海因里希·赫兹 (Heinrich Hertz) 的名字命名，他早在 1883 年就开始测量无线电波的频率。

                                                                                                    Inexpensive microprocessors might run at 20 MHz or so; more expensive processors for PCs run at more than 1 GHz. The unit of measurement is named after Heinrich Hertz, a German scientist who began measuring the frequency of radio waves back in 1883.

                                                                                                    这些芯片频率的理论上限是没有的；随着硅制造技术的进步，频率每年都在不断提高。如果你是一名无线电操作员，你可能会从无线电频谱中认出其中一些频率。今天的微处理器确实会在兆赫和千兆赫频段发射微小的无线电信号，这就是为什么计算机被屏蔽在金属盒中，以尽量减少对电视和收音机的干扰。

                                                                                                    There is no theoretical limit to how high these chip frequencies can go; it's been creeping up year after year with advances in silicon manufacturing technology. If you're a radio operator, you might recognize some of these frequencies from the radio spectrum. Today's microprocessors do indeed broadcast tiny radio signals in the megahertz and gigahertz bands, which is why computers are shielded in metal boxes to minimize interference with TVs and radios.



                                                                                                    最容易测量的是微处理器的时钟速度，也称为频率。芯片可能以 5 MHz、500 MHz 或 5,000 MHz 运行，但至少这是一个可验证的数字。不幸的是，它也毫无意义。微处理器的时钟速度就像汽车发动机的每分钟转数 (RPM)；当你加速时，它会发出悦耳的“嗖嗖”声，但它并不能告诉你任何有关实际马力的信息。大频率数字为广告和营销文献增添了吸引力，但它们并不是牛排。

                                                                                                    The easiest thing to measure is the clock speed of a microprocessor, also called its frequency. A chip might run at 5 MHz, 500 MHz, or 5,000 MHz, but at least it's a verifiable number. Unfortunately, it's also pretty meaningless. The clock speed of a microprocessor is like the revolutions per minute (RPM) of a car's engine; it makes a nice "zoom, zoom" noise when you rev it up, but it doesn't tell you anything about real horsepower. Big frequency numbers add sizzle to advertisements and marketing literature, but they're not the steak.

                                                                                                    为了试图理顺这种混乱局面，许多人创建了称为基准的特殊计算机程序。基准指示微处理器执行重复任务，然后测量完成任务所需的时间。它们是微处理器版的直线加速赛。（基准一词源于木匠在工作台上刻划间距规则的标记以测量材料的古老习惯。）

                                                                                                    To try to bring order to this chaos, a number of people have created special computer programs called benchmarks. Benchmarks instruct a microprocessor to perform repetitive tasks and then measure the time it took to finish them. They are the microprocessor equivalent of drag racing. (The word benchmark comes from an ages-old carpenters' habit of cutting regularly spaced marks on a workbench to measure materials.)

                                                                                                    就其本身而言，基准是很好的，但人们往往对其解读过度。就像汽车上的每加仑英里数 (MPG) 标签一样，基准只是一个估计值。您的里程可能会有所不同。即使估计值是正确的，一个数字也无法告诉您有关整个产品的信息。

                                                                                                    Benchmarks are fine, as far as they go, but people often read too much into them. Like the miles per gallon (MPG) sticker on a car, benchmarks are only an estimate. Your mileage may vary. Even if the estimate is correct, one number can't tell you very much about the whole product.

                                                                                                    技术讲座

                                                                                                    Tech Talk

                                                                                                    测量 Dhrystone MIPS

                                                                                                    Measuring Dhrystone MIPS

                                                                                                    DEC 公司于 1978 年制造了一台名为 VAX 11/780 的计算机，这是第一台每秒执行 100 万条指令的计算机。（事实证明这并不属实，但那是另一个故事了。）不久之后，其他计算机公司也想证明他们的产品与 VAX 一样快。

                                                                                                    DEC made a computer called the VAX 11/780, which was the first computer to perform 1 million instructions per second, in 1978. (This turned out to be untrue, but that's another story.) It wasn't long before other computer companies wanted to prove their products were as fast as the VAX.

                                                                                                    他们寻找一种易于翻译成不同类型计算机的程序，最终选中了 Dhrystone。VAX 每秒运行 Dhrystone 程序 1,757 次。这设定了标准。现在，任何每秒运行次数超过 1,757 次的计算机都被认为比 VAX 更快。

                                                                                                    They looked for a program that was easy to translate for different types of computers, and Dhrystone was selected. The VAX happened to run the Dhrystone program 1,757 times per second. This set the bar. Now any computer that could do more than 1,757 runs per second was judged to be faster than a VAX.

                                                                                                    奇怪的是，每秒 1,757 次 Dhrystone 运算这一神奇数字开始被用作 1 MIPS 的定义。无论计算机是否真的每秒执行 100 万条指令 (1 MIPS)，Dhrystone 分数都会被用作证据。即使是速度超过 1 MIPS 的计算机也会根据其 Dhrystone 性能降级为 1 MIPS。今天仍在使用相同的标度。

                                                                                                    Bizarrely, the magic number of 1,757 Dhrystone runs per second began to be used as the definition of 1 MIPS. Whether a computer was really performing 1 million instructions per second (1 MIPS) or not, the Dhrystone score was used as proof. Even computers that were faster than 1 MIPS were downgraded to 1 MIPS based on their Dhrystone performance. The same scale is still used today.



                                                                                                    误导性的 MIPS

                                                                                                    Misleading MIPS

                                                                                                    如果你乐观一点，MIPS 代表“每秒数百万条指令”。如果你持怀疑态度，那么它就是“销售人员毫无意义的性能指标”。长期以来，MIPS 数字是衡量微处理器性能的公认方法。随着时间的推移，它逐渐变得不再有用，而且肯定不再能衡量任何有用的东西。

                                                                                                    If you're optimistic, MIPS stands for "millions of instructions per second." If you're cynical, it's "meaningless indicator of performance for salesmen." The MIPS number was for a long time the accepted way to measure a microprocessor's performance. Over time it has slowly outgrown is usefulness and it certainly does not measure anything useful anymore.

                                                                                                    早期的计算机工程师自然喜欢将他们最新的计算机与竞争对手的机器进行比较。为此，他们会计算每台计算机每秒可以执行的指令数。每秒执行的指令越多，计算机就越快。在 20 世纪 70 年代，执行速度达到 1 MIPS 是一项巨大的成就，就像突破音障一样。

                                                                                                    Early computer engineers naturally liked to compare their latest computers with their rivals' machines. To do this, they'd count the number of instructions each computer could execute per second. The more instructions per second, the faster the computer. In the 1970s, performing at 1 MIPS was a big achievement, like breaking the sound barrier.

                                                                                                    如今的个人电脑和游戏中的微处理器每秒可以轻松完成数亿条指令，而且成本比早期的计算机要低。然而，它们并不是同一种指令，因此将今天的计算机与昨天的计算机进行比较并不公平。这就像将现代一级方程式赛车与历史悠久的自行车比赛进行比较。当然，现代赛车手在赛道上的速度更快，但这能证明什么呢？

                                                                                                    Today's microprocessors in PCs and games can easily polish off hundreds of millions of instructions per second, and for less money than those early computers. However, they aren't the same kind of instructions, so comparing today's computers to yesterday's isn't really fair. It's like comparing a modern Formula 1 auto race to a historic bicycle race. Of course the modern racers go around the track faster, but what does that prove?

                                                                                                    出于同样的原因，比较不同微处理器的 MIPS 评级既不相关也不公平。所有微处理器都执行不同类型的指令（称为指令集），并且它们无法直接比较。甲阅读日语的速度可能比乙阅读法语的速度快，但这并不能告诉我们任何有关他们任何一方的信息。

                                                                                                    By the same token, it's not relevant, or fair, to compare the MIPS ratings of different microprocessors. All microprocessors execute different kinds of instructions (called their instruction set), and they're not directly comparable. Person A might be able to read Japanese faster than Person B can read French, but that doesn't tell us anything useful about either one of them.

                                                                                                    技术讲座

                                                                                                    Tech Talk

                                                                                                    如何发音和拼写MIPS

                                                                                                    How to Pronounceand SpellMIPS

                                                                                                    如果您真的想给同事留下深刻印象，请确保 MIPS 的发音和拼写始终以大写 S 结尾。不要被发现说“one MIPS”，因为没有这种东西。它始终是“one MIPS”，因为最后一个 S 代表“秒”，有点像英里每小时 ( MPH ) 中的 H。尽管听起来很有趣，“one MIPS”是正确的。

                                                                                                    If you really want to impress your colleagues, be sure you always pronounce and spell MIPS with the capital S on the end. Don't get caught saying "one MIP" because there's no such thing. It's always "one MIPS" because the final S stands for "seconds," sort of like the H in miles per hour (MPH). Even though it sounds funny, "one MIPS" is correct.



                                                                                                    神话般的 MIPS-per-MHz 比率

                                                                                                    The Mythical MIPS-per-MHz Ratio

                                                                                                    芯片制造商最喜欢的一个伎俩就是用 MIPS-per-MHz 比率来吹嘘其处理器的“效率”。显然，这个数字是通过将 MIPS 数量（如前所述，这可能是可疑的）除以芯片的时钟速度（以兆赫为单位）得出的。这个数字越大，芯片被认为越“高效”。

                                                                                                    One favorite trick of chip makers is to brag about the "efficiency" of their processors with a MIPS-per-MHz ratio. Obviously this number is derived by taking the number of MIPS (which might be suspect, as described earlier) and dividing by the chip's clock speed measured in megahertz. The larger this number is, the more "efficient" the chip is judged to be.

                                                                                                    这种方法存在一些问题。首先，没人关心。对于消费者来说，知道一块芯片每百万分之一秒提供更多的 MIPS（不管是多少）有什么价值？最终结果不是最重要的吗？将两个数字相乘 MIPS乘以兆赫兹可能有意义。用一个数字除以另一个数字是没有意义的。

                                                                                                    There are a few problems with this approach. First, nobody cares. Of what value is it to a consumer to know that one chip delivers more MIPS (whatever those are) per millionth of a second? Isn't the end result what matters? Multiplying the two numbersMIPS times megahertzmight make sense. Dividing one by the other is pointless.

                                                                                                    其次，MIPS 本身的定义比较模糊。它可能会衡量芯片每秒执行的数百万条指令，但可能并非如此。更可能基于 Dhrystone 或其他基准，或从包含竞争对手分数的帽子中得出。即使使用真实的 MIPS 数字，这也不是工作、效率或前进的有用指标。

                                                                                                    Second, there's the squishy definition of MIPS itself. It might measure how many millions of instructions the chip executes per second, but probably not. More likely it's based on Dhrystone, or another benchmark, or drawn from a hat containing competitors' scores. Even if the true MIPS number is used, that's not a useful indication of work, efficiency, or forward progress.

                                                                                                    最后，该比率是自我定义的；它是一个循环引用。芯片制造商通常通过将微处理器的频率（兆赫）乘以某个秘密数字来定义其 MIPS 等级，本质上是反转 MIPS/MHz 公式。只有两个数字，其中一个是可疑的，MIPS/MHz 比率实际上是“兆赫乘以我们在营销部门编造的某个数字”的比率。

                                                                                                    Finally, the ratio is self-defining; it's a circular reference. Chip makers often define the MIPS rating for their microprocessor by multiplying its frequency (megahertz) by some secret number, essentially reversing the MIPS/MHz equation. With only two numbers, and one of them suspect, the MIPS/MHz ratio is really the "megahertz multiplied by some number we made up in the marketing department" ratio.

                                                                                                    功耗和 MIPS/瓦特

                                                                                                    Power Consumption and MIPS/Watt

                                                                                                    最近，设计微处理器芯片以尽可能减少耗电量已成为一种时尚。对于笔记本电脑等电池供电的设备来说，这样做的动机显而易见。电池使用时间越长，客户就越满意。较低的功耗也意味着更少的热量，有时热量比电池寿命更成问题。同样，客户不会喜欢一台太热而无法触摸的笔记本电脑。

                                                                                                    Lately it's become fashionable to design microprocessor chips so that they use the least amount of electricity possible. For battery-operated devices like laptop computers, the motivation for this is obvious. The longer the battery lasts, the happier the customer is. Lower power consumption also means less heat, and sometimes heat is a bigger problem than battery life. Again, customers won't be happy with a laptop computer that gets too hot to touch.

                                                                                                    出于这些原因和其他原因，工程师们在将高端微处理器的功耗降低到可控水平方面取得了快速进展。因此，这些芯片制造商自然也想向客户和媒体吹嘘他们的进步。可惜的是，测量功耗与测量性能一样困难。测量耗电量这项看似简单的任务已成为交战微处理器公司的战场。

                                                                                                    For these reasons and others, engineers have made rapid progress toward reducing the power consumption of high-end microprocessors to manageable levels. It naturally follows, then, that these same chip makers want to trumpet their advancements to their customers and the press. Alas, measuring power consumption is fraught with as many difficulties as measuring performance. The seemingly straightforward task of measuring electrical consumption has become a battlefield among warring microprocessor companies.

                                                                                                    最常见的功率效率测量方法是 MIPS-per-watt 比率。正如我们刚刚看到的 MIPS-per-MHz，这两个数字中的第一个数字从一开始就不可靠。遗憾的是，第二个数字可能同样不稳定。测量处理器的功耗并不容易，因为它一直在变化。芯片使用的电量取决于它正在做什么。如果您愿意，很容易想象出一种处理器相对空闲（消耗很少的能量）的情况。也很容易想象出处理器非常繁忙并且消耗更多电量的情况。这并不奇怪。您的电视在打开时比关闭时消耗更多电量。您测量哪种情况？

                                                                                                    The most common measure of power efficiency is the MIPS-per-watt ratio. As we just saw with MIPS-per-MHz, the first of these two numbers is unreliable to begin with. Sadly, the second number can be just as erratic. Measuring the power usage of a processor isn't easy because it changes all the time. The amount of electricity the chip uses depends on what it's doing. It's easy to invent a situation where the processor is relatively idlevacationing, if you willand consuming little energy. It's also easy to concoct situations where the processor is fantastically busy and consuming far more electricity. This shouldn't be surprising. Your TV uses more power when it's turned on than when it's turned off. Which condition do you measure?

                                                                                                    这取决于它大部分时间是开着还是关着。（但愿是后者。）还取决于您想知道总功耗（例如，一个月内）还是瞬时功耗（例如，10 秒内）。同样，处理器的功耗可以调到几乎任何适合其推广者的数字。

                                                                                                    That depends on whether it's turned on or turned off most of the time. (Let's hope it's the latter.) It also depends on whether you want to know overall power consumption (e.g., over the duration of a month) or instantaneous power consumption (e.g., for a period of 10 seconds). In the same way, a processor's power consumption can be dialed in to nearly any number that suits its promoters.

                                                                                                    因此，我们只剩下一个可疑数字（MIPS）除以另一个可疑数字（功率瓦特），得出一个极其可疑的数字。由于它与任何有形或有用的东西都无关，芯片制造商不妨每两周测量一次弗隆。

                                                                                                    So we're left with one suspect number (MIPS) divided by another suspect number (watts of power) to produce a monumentally suspect number. Bearing, as it does, no relation to anything tangible or useful, chip makers might as well be measuring furlongs per fortnight.

                                                                                                      什么是软件？

                                                                                                      What Is Software?

                                                                                                      软件，或者说编程，是微处理器的本质所在。软件是一个虚构的词，意在表明它在某种程度上是硬件的对立面。每个人都知道硬件是什么：它是计算机、电视或小红车的螺母和螺栓。用半导体术语来说，硬件是硅、塑料和其他可以触摸的东西。另一方面，软件就像 CD 上的音乐或电视上的节目。它可能不是物理的，但它绝对是真实的。

                                                                                                      Software, or programming, is the essence of what makes microprocessors interesting. Software is a made-up word meant to indicate it's somehow the opposite of hardware. Everybody knows what hardware is: It's the nuts and bolts of a computer, television, or little red wagon. In semiconductor terms, hardware is silicon, plastic, and other things you can touch. Software, on the other hand, is like the music on a CD or the programming on your television. It might not be physical but it's definitely real.

                                                                                                      电视机、CD 播放器、食谱和用 12 种语言（没有一种是您自己的语言）印刷的宣传单只是软件交付方式的示例。对于微处理器芯片，软件通常以软盘、CD-ROM、无线电波（如电视和广播）、互联网或永久存储在 ROM 芯片中的形式提供。无论形式如何，软件都是微处理器的程序，就像电视节目是电视的程序一样。

                                                                                                      The TV set, the CD player, the cookbook, and the leaflet printed in 12 languages (none of them your own) are just examples of how the software is delivered. For microprocessor chips, software usually comes on floppy disks, CD-ROMs, over the airwaves (like TV and radio), over the Internet, or permanently stored in a ROM chip. Regardless of the form, software is the programming for microprocessors, just like TV shows are the programming for TVs.

                                                                                                      和电视节目一样，程序也需要有人来编写。通常，一个程序员团队会一起工作。有些编程团队甚至有导演和制片人，就像电影片场的制片厂一样。有时，一个程序员会独自工作，就像一个独立电影导演。和电影制作、摄影或录制音乐一样，有些人编写程序是为了赚钱，而另一些人则只是因为喜欢而利用业余时间编写程序。

                                                                                                      Like TV shows, programs have to be created by someone. Usually a team of programmers works together. Some programming teams even have directors and producers, just like studio productions on a movie lot. Other times a single programmer works alone, like an independent film auteur. Like filmmaking, photography, or recording music, some people write programs as a paying profession, whereas others do it in their spare time just because they love it.

                                                                                                      技术讲座

                                                                                                      Tech Talk

                                                                                                      你可以将程序称为软件，但说“软件程序”是多余的。创建软件称为编程，但程序员有时称自己为软件工程师。程序员（或软件工程师）说他们整天都在“编写代码”或简称为“编码”。在一天的编码结束时，程序员可能已经编写了一定数量的“代码行”，即向微处理器发出一定数量的指令。

                                                                                                      You can call programs software, but saying "software program" is redundant. Creating software is called programming, but programmers sometimes call themselves software engineers. Programmers (or software engineers) say they spend the day "writing code" or simply "coding." At the end of a day of coding, a programmer might have written a certain number of "lines of code," meaning a certain number of instructions to the microprocessor.

                                                                                                      与之相关的还有“固件”。固件是存储在芯片（硬件）中的软件，模糊了硬件和软件之间的区别。最后，“湿件”就是人类的大脑。

                                                                                                      In a related vein, there's also "firmware." Firmware is software stored in a chip (which is hardware), blurring the distinction between hardware and software. Finally, "wetware" is simply the human brain.



                                                                                                      程序和电影之间的一个区别是，电影可以在世界各地的任何电视（或电影院屏幕）上播放；而程序则不然。计算机程序总是为特定类型的计算机创建的。例如，为 Apple Macintosh 编写的程序无法在运行 Microsoft Windows 的 PC 上运行。程序员必须尽早决定程序是否应该在 PC、Macintosh、UNIX 工作站、Palm Pilot、任天堂视频游戏、防抱死制动系统、蜂窝电话或任何其他运行软件的平台上运行。您可以在任何 CD 播放器上播放音乐 CD，但只能在正确类型的计算机上“播放”计算机程序。

                                                                                                      One difference between programs and movies is that movies can be played on any TV (or cinema screen) around the world; this is not so for programs. Computer programs are always created for a specific type of computer. Programs written for an Apple Macintosh, for example, don't work on a PC running Microsoft Windows. A programmer has to decide early on whether the program should work on a PC, a Macintosh, a UNIX workstation, a Palm Pilot, a Nintendo video game, an antilock brake system, a cellular telephone, or any of a thousand other platforms for running software. You can play music CDs on any CD player, but you can only "play" computer programs on the right kind of computer.

                                                                                                      所有这些不兼容的原因是什么？如果所有程序都可以在任何微处理器上运行，世界可能会变得更美好，但事实并非如此。每个不同的微处理器芯片都设计为理解不同的指令集（显然称为指令集）。就像说俄语或斯瓦希里语一样，不同的芯片只是说不同的语言，而且没有一个是双语的。为一种类型的微处理器芯片编写的程序被任何其他类型的微处理器芯片解释为胡言乱语。

                                                                                                      What's the reason for all this incompatibility? The world might be a better place if programs could all work on any microprocessor, but that's not the way it is. Each different microprocessor chip is designed to understand a different set of instructions (called, obviously enough, its instruction set). Like speaking Russian or Swahili, different chips simply speak different languages, and none of them are bilingual. Programs created for one type of microprocessor chip are interpreted as gibberish by any other type of microprocessor chip.

                                                                                                      有些芯片系列都理解同一种语言并运行相同的程序。例如，奔腾系列的芯片都运行相同的程序。这就是为什么新旧 PC 可以运行相同的 PC 程序。AMD 的 Athlon 和 Opteron 产品线的微处理器也属于奔腾系列，因此它们也可以运行 PC 程序。但是，SPARC 系列的芯片（仅举一个例子）无法运行 PC 程序，因为 SPARC 微处理器的指令集与奔腾系列微处理器不同。

                                                                                                      There are families of chips that all understand the same language and run the same programs. Chips in the Pentium family, for example, all run the same programs. That's why old and new PCs can run the same PC programs. Microprocessors from AMD's Athlon and Opteron product lines are also part of the Pentium family, so they can also run PC programs. However, chips from the SPARC family (to pick just one example) cannot run PC programs because SPARC microprocessors have a different instruction set from Pentium-family microprocessors.

                                                                                                      如果一个程序员团队希望他们的程序能够同时在奔腾系列处理器和 SPARC 系列处理器上运行，他们必须编写两次程序或使用称为交叉编译器的自动化工具将程序从一种指令集转换到另一种指令集。

                                                                                                      If a team of programmers wants their program to work both on Pentium-family processors and SPARC-family processors, they have to either write the program twice or translate the program from one instruction set to the other using an automated tool called a cross-compiler.

                                                                                                        选择微处理器

                                                                                                        Choosing Microprocessors

                                                                                                        微处理器市场竞争异常激烈。市场上有 100 多种不同的 32 位微处理器，还有更多的 16 位、8 位和 4 位芯片在争夺低端市场。总共有大约 1,000 种不同的处理器在争夺数百万种不同的系统，从恒温器到热核武器。

                                                                                                        The market for microprocessors is enormously competitive. Well over 100 different 32-bit microprocessors are available, with even more 16-bit, 8-bit, and 4-bit chips competing for the low end. In all, about 1,000 different processors are competing over millions of different systems, from thermostats to thermonuclear weapons.

                                                                                                        矛盾的是，这种技术含量最高的产品却在非技术性方面展开竞争。在高端市场，认知和广告对购买决策和市场成功有着重大影响。PC 处理器就是一个典型例子：电视广告敦促（可能）非技术观众购买他们不了解的产品。广告中甚至没有一丝技术材料。它们全都与形象和品牌知名度有关。当信息失效时，形象占上风。

                                                                                                        Paradoxically, this most technical of products competes on very nontechnical grounds. At the high end of the market, perception and advertising have a big influence on buying decisions and market success. The ultimate example is PC processors: Television advertisements urge (presumably) nontechnical viewers to buy a product they don't understand. The ads don't contain even a hint of technical material. They're all about image and brand-name recognition. When information fails, image prevails.

                                                                                                        32 位嵌入式微处理器市场对形象的关注程度略低。MIPS 和 ARM 等处理器系列之所以成功，是因为它们被视为安全的选择，被数十家客户使用和采用，没有明显的抱怨。尽管存在许多其他 32 位替代方案，其中一些甚至可能在技术上更胜一筹，但它们的优势并不总是足以打破市场领导者的形象。

                                                                                                        The 32-bit embedded microprocessor market is only a little less image-conscious. Processor families like MIPS and ARM are successful because they're perceived as safe choices, used and adopted by dozens of clients with no apparent complaints. Even though many other 32-bit alternatives exist, some of which might even be technically superior, their advantages aren't always compelling enough to break through the image of the market leaders.

                                                                                                        软件兼容性

                                                                                                        Software Compatibility

                                                                                                        最重要的是，微处理器业务是由软件决定的。大多数买家选择微处理器不是看硬件的优点，而是看软件的优势。由于每个微处理器系列都有自己特殊的指令集，为一个微处理器系列编写的程序不能在另一个微处理器系列上运行，因此选择微处理器也意味着选择适用于该微处理器的软件。对于大多数买家来说，这是本末倒置。他们宁愿先决定自己想要什么软件，然后选择一个能与该软件配合使用的微处理器。

                                                                                                        Most of all, the microprocessor business is determined by software. Most buyers choose a microprocessor not by the merits of its hardware, but by the advantages of its software. Because every microprocessor family has its own special instruction set, and programs written for one microprocessor family cannot run on another, it follows that choosing a microprocessor also means choosing the software that's available for it. For most buyers, that's putting the cart before the horse. They'd rather decide what software they want, and then choose a microprocessor that works with that software.

                                                                                                        选择微处理器有点像选择要学习的新语言。掌握任何新语言都需要付出同样的努力，因此您通常会选择一种广泛使用的语言（西班牙语、法语或普通话）、一种与您的兴趣领域相关的语言（歌手的意大利语）或一种当地流行的语言（密尔沃基的德语或圣何塞的越南语）。选择与语言的表现力或其他品质无关；它更多地与其在外部世界中的地位有关。同样，买家会选择广泛使用的、适合其应用程序的或在其公司或行业中根深蒂固的微处理器。这与硬件的位数、架构或任何其他内在品质几乎没有关系。

                                                                                                        Choosing a microprocessor is a bit like choosing a new language to study. Any new language requires about the same amount of effort to master, so you generally choose one that's widely used (Spanish, French, or Mandarin), one that's related to your area of interest (Italian for singers), or one that's locally popular (German in Milwaukee or Vietnamese in San Jose). The choice has nothing to do with the expressive power of the language or its other qualities; it has more to do with its place in the outside world. Similarly, buyers choose microprocessors that are in wide use, suited to their applications, or entrenched within their company or industry. This has little to do with bittedness, architecture, or any other intrinsic qualities of the hardware.

                                                                                                        这种从众心理的缺点是，它使新产品的差异化变得更加困难。如果你选择了一种特定的微处理器，因为你所在行业中的其他人已经这样做了，那么你与竞争对手并没有什么不同。你获得了软件基础，​​但失去了硬件优势。在最坏的情况下，你只能通过塑料颜色来区分你的产品（在某些情况下确实如此）。更乐观的是，你可以为原创产品创建新的软件。额外的软件可以增加竞争对手所没有的功能，从而掩盖硬件的底层相似性。

                                                                                                        The downside of this herd instinct is that it makes it harder to differentiate a new product. If you've chosen a particular microprocessor because others in your industry have done so, you're no different from your competitors. You've gained a software foundation but lost a hardware advantage. In the worst case, you differentiate your product by the color of its plastic (literally true in some cases). More optimistically, you can create new software for the product that's original. The additional software can add features your competitors don't have, masking the underlying similarities in the hardware.

                                                                                                          微处理器未来趋势

                                                                                                          Microprocessor Future Trends

                                                                                                          毫无疑问，微处理器将随着时间的推移变得越来越复杂。我们远未达到微处理器增长的自然极限。曾经，设计单片计算机似乎很愚蠢——毕竟，世界需要多少台计算机？现在，停止设计单片计算机似乎同样荒谬。

                                                                                                          There's no question that microprocessors will continue to grow more complex over time. We're nowhere near reaching any natural limit to microprocessor growth. Where once it seemed silly to design a computer-on-a-chipafter all, how many computers does the world neednow it seems just as absurd to stop.

                                                                                                          微处理器芯片的实际尺寸增长缓慢，但其内部的复杂性增长速度却快得多，因为半导体技术允许工程师在更小的空间内塞入更多晶体管。仅几年后，拥有 100 万个晶体管的微处理器就被拥有 1 亿个晶体管的处理器所超越。拥有 1 亿个晶体管的微处理器也紧随其后。这种趋势仍在继续，而且看不到尽头。

                                                                                                          The actual size of microprocessor chips is growing only slowly, but the complexity within them is growing much faster because semiconductor technology permits engineers to squeeze more transistors into less space. Microprocessors with 1 million transistors were surpassed by 10-million-transistor processors after only a few years. Microprocessors with 100 million transistors weren't far behind. This trend continues with no end in sight.

                                                                                                          更大的问题是：工程师们将如何填补这个空白？他们将如何花费 5 亿个晶体管的预算？答案历来来自上层，来自大型机系统和超级计算机。几十年来，微处理器一直紧随高端计算机的发展，最初落后几代，但现在仅落后高端计算机几年。多年来，微处理器一直紧随计算机制造商的脚步，这就是为什么许多大型计算机公司在 20 世纪 90 年代倒闭的原因。一些计算机制造商没有逆潮流而动，而是加入了潮流，围绕商用微处理器设计他们的机器，但随后却很难将他们的产品与采用相同策略并使用相同芯片的其他公司的产品区分开来。

                                                                                                          The bigger question is this: How will engineers fill the space? How will they spend their 500-million-transistor budgets? The answer has historically come from above, from mainframe systems and supercomputers. For decades, microprocessors shadowed the developments of high-end computers, first lagging by several generations but now lagging the high-end machines by only a few years. Microprocessors have been nipping at the heels of the computer makers for years, which is why so many big computer companies went out of business in the 1990s. Rather than fight the trend, some computer makers joined the bandwagon and designed their machines around commercial microprocessors, but then had a hard time differentiating their products from other companies with the same strategy and access to the same chips.

                                                                                                          未来的趋势是合作。尽管微处理器每年的速度提高约 30%，但它们所做的有用工作并没有那么多。未来的芯片可能不会更快地执行单个任务，而是可能会同时执行更多任务，但速度会更慢。一个由 12 名砌砖工组成的团队比一个速度很快的砌砖工单独工作效率更高。同样，多个微处理器团队共同解决问题可能会产生更好的晶体管投资回报。

                                                                                                          Future trends point toward cooperation. Even though microprocessors get about 30 percent faster every year, they're not doing that much more useful work. Instead of performing single tasks even faster, future chips are likely to perform more simultaneous tasks, but slower. A team of 12 bricklayers is more productive than one really fast bricklayer working alone. By the same token, teams of microprocessors working on a problem together will likely generate a better return on the investment of transistors.

                                                                                                          单芯片内的协作是一种可行的方法。如今的微处理器可以并行执行几条指令，这种技术被称为指令级并行 (ILP)。不过，这种方法不可能永远发展下去。超标量处理器可能变得非常复杂，以至于它们无法提供足够的额外性能，不值得花费额外的硅片。ILP 已经将微处理器推向了它所能达到的极限。它在过去几年里一直很有效，但这种方法正在失去动力。

                                                                                                          Cooperation within a single chip is one way to go. Called instruction-level parallelism (ILP), microprocessors today can execute a few instructions in parallel. This approach can't grow forever, though. Superscalar processors can become so complex that they don't deliver enough extra performance to be worth the extra silicon. ILP has already moved microprocessors about as far forward as it can. It has worked for the past few years, but it's an approach that's running out of steam.

                                                                                                          另一种方法是将问题转移到芯片之外。芯片级对称多处理 (SMP) 有望使许多微处理器协同工作。大型超级计算机已经实现了这一点，其理论依据是两个（或更多）脑袋比一个脑袋好。同时使用多个芯片也有经济优势。单个微处理器不必那么大（也就是说昂贵），而且在升级时可以在系统中添加或删除处理器。问题主要在于软件。编写具有多个处理器的计算机程序并不是一件容易的事，就像指挥同一间厨房里的多个厨师一样困难。到目前为止，很少有程序员能够展现出协调如此强大的计算能力的才能。

                                                                                                          Taking the problem outside the chip is another approach. Chip-level symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) promises to keep many microprocessors working in concert. Large supercomputers do this already, on the theory that two (or more) heads are better than one. Using several chips together has economic advantages, too. Individual microprocessors won't have to be so large (read: expensive) and it might be possible to add or remove processors from a system when upgrading. The problems lie mainly in the software. It's not trivial to program a computer with multiple processors, any more than it is to command multiple cooks working in the same kitchen. Orchestrating that much computing horsepower is a talent few programmers have thus far demonstrated.

                                                                                                          随着芯片复杂度的增加，RISC 概念似乎逐渐失去吸引力。矛盾的是，RISC 设计理念的出现正值晶体管预算不断增加之际。既然晶体管几乎免费，为什么要节省硅片呢？既然程序员稀缺且薪水很高，为什么要把负担放在软件上呢？芯片设计师已经了解到，他们可以让他们的微处理器更复杂，同时还能让它们运行得更快。我们也可以鱼与熊掌兼得。无论哪种架构方法占据主导地位，明天的微处理器肯定会比今天的更复杂。

                                                                                                          RISC concepts seem to be slowly losing currency as chip complexity increases. Paradoxically, the RISC design philosophy arose just as transistor budgets were expanding. Why economize on silicon when transistors are almost free? Why put the burden on software when programmers are scarce and highly paid? Chip designers have learned they can make their microprocessors more complex and still have them run faster. We get to have our cake and eat it, too. Whichever architectural approach gains prominence, tomorrow's microprocessors are guaranteed to be more complex than today's.

                                                                                                          另一个保证是微处理器将变得更加普遍。在 20 世纪初期，电动机是稀有而珍贵的商品（家用电力也是如此）。目录和干货商店为可能只有一台电动机的家庭主妇出售各种各样的附件和附加装置。如今，电动机在搅拌机、磁带播放器、冷却风扇和行政玩具中如此普遍，以至于我们不会注意到它们。如果它们磨损或损坏，我们会将它们扔掉，因为修理它们不值得。

                                                                                                          The other guarantee is that microprocessors will become even more ubiquitous. In the early 1900s electric motors were rare and precious commodities (so was home electricity). Catalogs and dry-good stores sold myriad attachments and add-ons for householders who presumably had only one electrical motor in the home, if that. Today, electric motors are so prevalent in blenders, tape players, cooling fans, and executive toys that we don't notice them. If they wear out or break we throw them away because it's not worth the effort to repair them.

                                                                                                          未来的微处理器将从无处不在变成无处不在。一部普通的手机将不止装一两个微处理器，而是会有 15 个。汽车将成为流动的计算机农场。儿童玩具将成为 NASA 太空计划羡慕的对象。口香糖机将提供 64 位纪念品，只要你挥动你的计算机借记卡。微处理器将像人行道上的硬币：闪闪发光、引人入胜，但不值得从地上捡起来。

                                                                                                          Tomorrow's microprocessors will go from being in everything to being in everything many times over. The average cellular telephone won't have one or two microprocessors in it; it will have 15. Cars will become rolling computer farms. Children's toys will be the envy of the NASA space program. Gumball machines will dispense 64-bit souvenirs, after you wave your computerized debit card in its general direction. Microprocessors will be like pennies on the sidewalk: shiny and interesting but not worth picking up off the ground.

                                                                                                            第七章 记忆的基本指南

                                                                                                            Chapter 7. Essential Guide to Memory

                                                                                                            在本章中...

                                                                                                            In this chapter...

                                                                                                            • 内存芯片概述

                                                                                                            • Overview of Memory Chips

                                                                                                            • 非易失性 ROM

                                                                                                            • Nonvolatile ROM

                                                                                                            • 易失性 RAM

                                                                                                            • Volatile RAM

                                                                                                            • 内存接口

                                                                                                            • Memory Interfaces

                                                                                                            • 未来的记忆

                                                                                                            • Future Memories

                                                                                                              内存芯片概述

                                                                                                              Overview of Memory Chips

                                                                                                              内存芯片是数量最多的芯片之一，占全球半导体出货量和销售额的很大一部分。它们以数百万计的速度生产和销售，几乎每个装有芯片的电子产品都至少有一个内存芯片。计算机是内存芯片的最大用户。大多数个人电脑至少有八个内存芯片，通常有二十几个或更多。内存芯片还引领了芯片制造的新进步。新的硅技术在用于其他任何地方之前都会在内存芯片上进行试验。

                                                                                                              Memory chips are among the most plentiful kind of chips, making up a big part of semiconductor shipments and sales around the world. They're produced and sold by the millions and nearly every electronic item that has any kind of chip in it has at least one memory chip as well. Computers are the biggest users of memory chips. Most PCs have at least eight memory chips, and they often contain two dozen or more. Memory chips also lead the way in new advances in chip manufacturing. New silicon technologies are tried out on memory chips before they're used anywhere else.

                                                                                                              众所周知，芯片制造技术一直在进步、速度越来越快、越来越先进，这一点在内存芯片领域表现得最为明显。事实上，内存芯片经常被用作衡量整个半导体行业进步的标尺。它们是衡量其他芯片的标准。

                                                                                                              Chip manufacturing gets better, faster, and more advanced all the time, as we know, and nowhere is this more evident than in memory chips. In fact, memory chips are often used as the yardstick for the whole semiconductor industry's progress. They're the standard by which other chips are measured.

                                                                                                              尽管内存芯片非常先进，但它也是所有芯片中最便宜的。尽管内存芯片不断变得更好、更快、更高效，但它似乎从未变得更贵。正是这种功能的不断增加（或价格的螺旋式下降，这取决于你的观点）比其他任何事情都更能导致电子产品入侵我们家中、汽车和口袋中的日常低成本物品。如果内存不是这么便宜，微处理器、个人电脑、手机和视频游戏也不会这么便宜。

                                                                                                              As advanced as they are, memory chips are also among the cheapest of all chips. Even though they continually get better, faster, and more efficient, memory chips never seem to get more expensive. It's this constant increase in functionality (or spiraling decrease in price, depending on your perspective) that has, more than anything else, led to the invasion of electronics into everyday low-cost items in our homes, cars, and pockets. If memory wasn't so cheap, microprocessors, PCs, cell phones, and video games wouldn't be so inexpensive, either.

                                                                                                              关于内存芯片

                                                                                                              About Memory Chips

                                                                                                              众所周知，内存芯片存储数据。它们以比特的形式以电子方式存储数据。一个内存比特只是少量的电。每个比特要么带电荷，要么不带电荷；没有中间状态。这让内存芯片的工作变得轻松。每个比特要么这样，要么那样：要么黑，要么白，要么上，要么下，要么真，要么假，要么一，要么零。当只有两个选项时，记住一个比特是相当容易的。

                                                                                                              As you know, memory chips store data. They do this electronically in the form of bits. A bit of memory is simply a tiny amount of electricity. Each bit either has an electric charge or it doesn't; there's no in between. That makes life easy for the memory chip. Each bit is either one way or the other: either black or white, up or down, true or false, one or zero. It's pretty easy to remember a bit when there are only two options.

                                                                                                              内存芯片中的每一位存储都使用芯片上的少量硅。内存芯片越大，可以存储的位数就越多。过去 30 年来，内存芯片的存储容量急剧增长，从存储 1,000 位的芯片到如今存储 10 亿位的芯片，提高了数百万倍。然而，尽管如此，内存价格却出人意料地保持平稳。

                                                                                                              Each bit of storage in a memory chip uses a small amount of silicon on the chip. The bigger the memory chip, the more bits it can store. The storage capacity of memory chips has grown dramatically over the past 30 years, from chips that held 1,000 bits to today's chips, which hold 1 billion bitsa million-fold improvement. Yet for all that, memory prices have remained surprisingly flat.

                                                                                                              如果你在制造内存芯片，你会试图将每个比特压缩到尽可能小的空间中以节省硅片。如果每个比特再小一点，一百万比特的芯片就会小得多，制造成本也更低。内存价格相当有竞争力，因此即使比竞争对手有微小的尺寸或成本优势，也可以在几个月的生产中带来数百万美元的额外利润。内存制造商从未停止尝试将晶体管做得更小或将它们紧密地排列在一起。与任何商品一样，制造效率的微小差异可能会转化为利润的巨大差异。

                                                                                                              If you're making memory chips, you try to squeeze each bit into as little space as possible to save silicon. If each bit is even slightly smaller, a million-bit chip will be significantly smaller and cheaper to manufacture. Memory prices are quite competitive, so even a tiny size or cost advantage over your competitors can spell millions of dollars of extra profit over a few months of production. Memory makers never stop trying to make transistors slightly smaller or pack them closer together. As with any commodity, small differences in manufacturing efficiency can translate into big differences in the bottom line.

                                                                                                              内存制造商之间不断的压力和竞争，以及缺乏任何大的差异化功能，使得这些芯片的价格一直处于低位。图 7.1显示了内存每比特成本在几代硅片技术中如何大幅下降。如果每比特成本下降，则给定类型内存芯片的成本也会随之下降。昂贵的内存芯片很快就会变成廉价的内存芯片，然后完全从市场上消失。内存芯片的商业保质期仅比浪漫小说长一点。

                                                                                                              The constant pressure and competition among memory makers and the lack of any big differentiating features has kept the prices of these chips consistently low. Figure 7.1 shows how the cost per bit of memory has plummeted over several generations of silicon technology. If the cost per bit falls, the cost for a given type of memory chip falls with it. Expensive memory chips quickly become cheap memory chips, and then disappear from the market completely. The commercial shelf life of memory chips is only slightly longer than that of romance novels.

                                                                                                              图 7.1. 自 1970 年制造出第一块 DRAM 芯片以来，制造 1 百万位 (1 Mbit) 半导体存储器芯片的成本已下降了 100 万倍。巧合的是，DRAM 芯片的容量在同一时间内增长了 100 万倍。

                                                                                                              尽管每比特成本大幅下降，但每块芯片的比特数却飞速上升。最终结果是新内存芯片的价格多年来一直保持相当稳定。你只是用钱买到了更好的东西。

                                                                                                              Even as the cost per bit sinks like a rock, the number of bits per chip rises like a rocket. The net effect is that the price of a new memory chip has remained remarkably constant for years. You just get more for your money.

                                                                                                              存储芯片有几种标准尺寸或容量，就像牛奶盒一样。您不能像买香蕉一样随意购买适合自己的存储位数；您必须从几种标准尺寸中进行选择。每个新存储芯片的容量通常都是之前芯片的四倍。例如，您可能会发现同时有存储 6400 万位、25600 万位和 102400 万位的芯片在售。如果您真正想要的是 28800 万位的芯片，那么您就没那么幸运了，您将不得不为 102400 万位的芯片付费。

                                                                                                              Memory chips are sold in several standard sizes, or capacities, like cartons of milk. You can't buy an arbitrary number of memory bits like bananas to suit yourself; you have to choose from among a few standard sizes. Each new memory chip usually offers four times the capacity of the chip that came before it. For example, you might find chips that store 64 million bits, 256 million bits, and 1,024 million bits for sale at the same time. If what you really wanted was a 288-million-bit chip, you're out of luck and you will have to pay for the 1,024-million-bit chip.

                                                                                                              除了容量之外，内存芯片之间唯一的区别就是速度。有些内存芯片的数据检索速度比其他芯片快。大容量芯片通常比小容量芯片慢（因为它们必须搜索更长时间）。有些客户愿意为更快的内存芯片支付高价，但有些客户则不会。如果你是内存制造商，你必须决定是将芯片设计为最大容量（使其速度变慢）还是速度（使其容量变小）。平衡是一项微妙的工作，它取决于难以预测的市场条件。

                                                                                                              Apart from capacity, the only thing that differentiates one memory chip from another is speed. Some memory chips can retrieve their data faster than others. Large-capacity chips are generally slower than small-capacity chips (because they have to search longer). Some customers will pay a price premium for faster memory chips, but others won't. If you're a memory maker, you have to decide whether to design your chips for maximum capacity (making them slower) or for speed (making them less capacious). The balancing act is a delicate one, and it depends on market conditions, which are difficult to predict.

                                                                                                              记忆类型

                                                                                                              Types of Memory

                                                                                                              内存芯片有两种基本类型：永久性和非永久性。永久性芯片可以永久存储数据位，即使电源关闭或与芯片断开连接也是如此。它们的内存可以在没有电池的情况下持续使用多年。另一方面，非永久性芯片仅在通电时工作。当您关闭或断开这些芯片的电源时，所有内存都会丢失。虽然这似乎毫无意义，但后者实际上是两者中更受欢迎的一类。

                                                                                                              Memory chips come in two basic types: permanent and impermanent. The permanent kind of chips store data bits forever, even after their electrical power has been turned off or disconnected from the chip. Their memory lasts for years and years without batteries. The impermanent kind, on the other hand, only works while the power is on. When you power down or disconnect these chips, all their memory is lost. Although that might seem pointless, the latter category is actually the more popular of the two.

                                                                                                              具有永久记忆的芯片称为非易失性记忆芯片。非永久记忆的芯片称为易失性记忆芯片。这并不意味着这些芯片会爆炸，只是它们的记忆很容易丢失。

                                                                                                              Chips with permanent memories are called nonvolatile memory chips. Impermanent memory chips are called volatile memory. That doesn't mean the chips are explosive, only that their memories are easily lost.

                                                                                                              另一种对内存芯片进行分类的方法是 ROM 与 RAM。基本只读存储器 (ROM) 不能被擦除或写入新数据。它是永久性的，就像一块石碑。您可以随时擦除和重新编程随机存取存储器 (RAM) 芯片。所有 RAM 芯片都是易失性的，如果不小心维护，它们的内存就会丢失。所有 ROM 芯片都是非易失性的，可以永久存储数据，但并非所有非易失性芯片都是 ROM；有些可以擦除或更改。明白了吗？

                                                                                                              Another way to categorize memory chips is by ROM versus RAM. Your basic read-only memory (ROM) can't be erased or have new data written into it. It's permanent, like a stone tablet. You can erase and reprogram a random-access memory (RAM) chip as often as you want. All RAM chips are volatile, losing their memories if not carefully tended. All ROM chips are nonvolatile, storing their data forever, but not all nonvolatile chips are ROMs; some can be erased or changed. Got it?

                                                                                                              RAM 芯片比 ROM 芯片更贵，但对于计算机、手持设备和大多数其他类似计算机的产品来说，RAM 芯片是必不可少的。微处理器需要一个可擦除的“工作区”，在其中执行计算并遵循编程指令。RAM 芯片提供了这种必要的容量。

                                                                                                              RAM chips are more expensive than ROM chips but they're indispensable for computers, handheld devices, and most other computer-like products. Microprocessors need an erasable "workspace" in which to perform their calculations and follow their programmed instructions. RAM chips provide this necessary capacity.

                                                                                                              ROM 比 RAM 便宜，可用于永久或半永久存储。ROM 芯片可用于存储永久数据，例如车库门开启器的安全代码或运行恒温器的微型程序。计算机还使用 ROM 芯片存储一些“刻在石头上”且永远不会丢失的永久程序，例如如何启动计算机以及如何访问软盘。

                                                                                                              ROMs are cheaper than RAMs and they are used for permanent or semipermanent storage. ROM chips are useful for storing permanent bits of data, such as the security code for your garage-door opener or the tiny program that runs a thermostat. Computers also use ROM chips to store some permanent programs that are "etched in stone" and should never be lost, such as how to start up the computer and how to access a floppy diskette.

                                                                                                                非易失性 ROM

                                                                                                                Nonvolatile ROM

                                                                                                                ROM 芯片有几种不同的类型。与所有内存芯片一样，ROM 的价格主要取决于容量，速度会略有溢价。有些 ROM 可以比其他 ROM 更快地检索数据，对于构建快速系统的人来说，这可能值得多花一点钱。

                                                                                                                ROM chips come in a few different types. Like all memory chips, ROM prices are based mostly on capacity, with a small price premium for speed. Some ROMs can retrieve data faster than others, and this might be worth a little extra money to someone building a fast system.

                                                                                                                掩膜版 ROM

                                                                                                                Masked ROM

                                                                                                                最简单、最便宜的 ROM 称为掩膜 ROM (MROM)。这些芯片是批量生产的，其中已经存储了特定的数据位。一旦 MROM 制作完成，数据就永远无法更改。这通常是关键所在：MROM 适用于汽车等批量生产的产品，其中的防抱死制动系统软件永远不能更改。

                                                                                                                The simplest and cheapest ROMs are called masked ROMs (MROMs). These chips are mass-produced with particular data bits already stored in them. Once the MROMs are made, the data can never be changed. This is usually the point: MROMs are good for mass-produced products like cars, in which the software for the antilock brake system should never be altered.

                                                                                                                由于 MROM 的数据模式在芯片制造时就已永久设定，因此仅会为大客户大批量生产。半导体制造商偶尔只生产几千个 ROM 并不划算。停止生产线并安装工具的成本高得令人望而却步。因此，尽管 MROM 是最便宜的 ROM 形式，但它们仅供大客户或最受欢迎的产品使用。

                                                                                                                Because their data patterns are permanently set when the chips are built, MROMs are only made in large volumes for big customers. It isn't cost-effective for a semiconductor maker to produce just a few thousand ROMs once in awhile. The cost of stopping the production line and setting up the tooling is prohibitive. So although MROMs are the cheapest form of ROMs, they're reserved for only the largest customers or the most popular products.

                                                                                                                可编程 ROM

                                                                                                                Programmable ROM

                                                                                                                对于普通消费者来说，一种更具成本效益的替代方案是可编程 ROM (PROM)。它们类似于 ROM 芯片，但它们是空白制造的，其中没有存储任何数据位。（从另一个角度看，所有位都是零。）然后，客户使用称为 PROM 刻录机的机器加载 PROM 的内容。只有一次机会对 PROM 进行编程；加载数据后，PROM 的内容是永久的。

                                                                                                                A more cost-effective alternative for the average consumer is the programmable ROM (PROM). These are like ROM chips but they are manufactured blank, with no data bits stored in them. (Viewed another way, all the bits are zeros.) The customer then loads the contents of the PROM using a machine called a PROM burner. There's only one chance to program a PROM; after the data has been loaded, the PROM's contents are permanent.

                                                                                                                由于 PROM 只能“烧录”一次，因此被称为一次性可编程 ROM (OTP ROM)。这些芯片是中型公司享受批量生产 ROM 低成本且无需承担大批量风险的好方法。公司可以随时储备空白 PROM，并在最后一刻烧录其内容。有时确实如此：畅销的电子产品有时会存放在仓库中，用电线挂在运输箱上。产品在装上卡车之前会进行最终编程。

                                                                                                                Because PROMs can only be "burned" once, they're called one-time programmable ROMs (OTP ROMs). These chips are a good way for medium-sized companies to enjoy the low cost of mass-produced ROMs without the risk of large volume commitments. Companies can keep a supply of blank PROMs in stock for as long as necessary, burning their contents at the last minute. Sometimes this is literally true: Fast-selling electronics goods are sometimes stored in the warehouse with a wire hanging from the shipping carton. The product receives its final programming just before it goes on the truck.

                                                                                                                可擦除可编程 ROM

                                                                                                                Erasable Programmable ROM

                                                                                                                成本与灵活性之间的下一个选择是可擦除可编程 ROM (EPROM)。与 ROM 和 PROM 不同，如果您有合适的设备，EPROM 是可以擦除的。EPROM 比 ROM 或 PROM 都贵，而且由于可能被擦除，所以不能用于某些安全要求严格的设备。不过，EPROM 在计算机和其他大批量产品中非常受欢迎，因为这些产品的标准和功能需要不时更改。

                                                                                                                The next step in the cost-versus-flexibility scale is the erasable programmable ROM (EPROM). Unlike ROMs and PROMs, EPROMs can be erased if you have the right equipment. EPROMs are more expensive than either ROMs or PROMs, and they can't be used in some safety-critical equipment because of the possibility of erasure. Still, EPROMs are extremely popular in computers and other high-volume products where standards and features need to change from time to time.

                                                                                                                EPROM 和 PROM 一样，都是空白制造和运输的。客户也使用 PROM 刻录机以同样的方式将数据位加载到其中。PROM 和 EPROM 之间的唯一区别是，如果将 EPROM 暴露在紫外线下足够长的时间，则可以擦除 EPROM。通常在特殊灯下放置 30 分钟就足以擦除 EPROM 并将其恢复到原始空白状态。

                                                                                                                EPROMs are manufactured and shipped blank, just like PROMs. Customers load data bits into them just the same way, too, using a PROM burner. The only difference between a PROM and an EPROM is that you can erase an EPROM if you expose it to ultraviolet light for long enough. Usually 30 minutes under a special lamp is enough to erase an EPROM and return it back to its original blank condition.

                                                                                                                这违反了我们之前关于 ROM 是永久性的且不可擦除的规则，但 EPROM 仍然符合 ROM 的条件。由于擦除和重新编程 EPROM 需要半小时或更长时间，因此这些芯片无法与 RAM 竞争，RAM 可以在几分之一秒内被擦除和重新编程。尽管 EPROM 可以被擦除，但它们仍然是非易失性的；除非故意擦除，否则存储在 EPROM 中的任何数据都会持续数年。

                                                                                                                This violates our earlier rule about ROMs being permanent and not erasable, but EPROMs still qualify as ROMs. Because it takes half an hour or more to erase and reprogram an EPROM, these chips do not compete with RAMs, which can be erased and reprogrammed in a fraction of a second. Even though EPROMs can be erased, they're still nonvolatile; any data stored in an EPROM will last for years unless it's deliberately erased.

                                                                                                                EPROM 的封装顶部有一个圆形小窗口（如图 7.2所示），用于让紫外线通过。该窗口允许光线直接照射到内部的硅芯片上。与大多数芯片不同，EPROM 芯片的设计对紫外线敏感，会逐渐失去其记忆力。

                                                                                                                EPROMs have a small round window on the top of their package, shown in Figure 7.2, to let ultraviolet light through. The window allows light to shine directly on the silicon chip inside. The EPROM chip, unlike most chips, is designed to be sensitive to ultraviolet light, gradually losing its memory.

                                                                                                                图 7.2。可擦除可编程只读存储器 (EPROM) 芯片顶部有一个窗口，可以露出下面的硅芯片。用紫外线照射这个窗口几分钟，就可以擦除芯片上存储的数据位。擦除后，可以用不同的数据重新编程芯片。图片由德州仪器提供。经许可使用。

                                                                                                                电可擦除可编程 ROM

                                                                                                                Electrically Erasable Programmable ROM

                                                                                                                电可擦除可编程 ROM (EEPROM) 比 EPROM 更先进，因为它们可以通过电子方式擦除，而不必暴露在紫外线下。这使得 EEPROM 芯片在许多系统中更易于使用。例如，EEPROM 可以永久焊接到印刷电路板上，并且无需移除即可擦除，而普通 EPROM 则必须从系统中移除并放在紫外线灯下。这使得 EEPROM 在 PC 和其他消费品中更加方便用户使用，因为这些产品中没有移除和擦除 EPROM 的工具和技能。

                                                                                                                Electrically erasable programmable ROMs (EEPROMs) are an advancement over EPROMs because they can be erased electronically, instead of through exposure to ultraviolet light. This makes EEPROM chips easier to use in many systems. For example, an EEPROM can be permanently soldered onto a printed circuit board and still be erased without removing it, whereas a normal EPROM would have to be removed from the system and placed under an ultraviolet lamp. This makes EEPROMs more user friendly in PCs and other consumer items where the tools and the skills to remove and erase an EPROM just aren't there.

                                                                                                                对于工程师来说，EEPROM 通常被称为 E 2 PROM 或“e-squared”。EEPROM 比传统的 EPROM 有许多有用的优势，但它们从未占据太多的市场份额，因为它们很快就被闪存 ROM 所取代，我们将在下文中介绍闪存 ROM。

                                                                                                                Typically for engineers, EEPROMs are often called E2PROMs, or "e-squareds." EEPROMs have many useful advantages over traditional EPROMs, but they never captured very much market share because they were quickly overtaken by flash ROMs, which are covered next.

                                                                                                                闪存

                                                                                                                Flash ROM

                                                                                                                闪存 ROM 是目前最流行的可擦除 ROM 类型（可擦除 ROM 并非矛盾的说法）。与 EEPROM 一样，闪存 ROM 可以完全以电子方式擦除和重新编程，而无需从系统中移除芯片。这使得闪存 ROM 非常适用于那些要求相对天真的客户在没有任何专业知识的情况下擦除和重新编程芯片的产品。MP3 音乐播放器和偶尔的 PC 都属于这一类。

                                                                                                                Flash ROMs are now the most popular type of erasable ROM (and no, erasable ROM is not really an oxymoron). Like EEPROMs, flash ROMs can be erased and reprogrammed completely electronically, without removing the chip from the system. This makes flash ROMs very useful in products for which a relatively naïve customer might be asked to erase and reprogram the chips without any specialized knowledge. MP3 music players and occasionally PCs fall into this category.

                                                                                                                闪存 ROM 与 EEPROM 的区别在于速度。正如其名称所示，EEPROM 擦除速度较慢，而闪存 ROM 则相当快。您可以在几秒钟内擦除并重新编程整个闪存 ROM，而传统 EEPROM 则需要几分钟。对于大多数消费产品而言，这种差异具有巨大的心理价值。客户通常对重新编程或更新其产品上的软件感到十分紧张；快速完成这些工作可以缓解很多紧张情绪。

                                                                                                                Where flash ROMs differ from EEPROMs is speed. EEPROMs are slow to erase but flash ROMs are pretty quick, as their name suggests. You can erase and reprogram an entire flash ROM in a few seconds, versus several minutes for a conventional EEPROM. For most consumer products, that difference has enormous psychological value. Customers are often nervous enough about reprogramming or updating the software on their products; getting it over with quickly alleviates a lot of tension.

                                                                                                                闪存 ROM 最初比 EEPROM 贵得多，而 EEPROM 又比 EPROM 贵得多，等等。自从闪存芯片首次开发以来的 10 年左右时间里，由于其容量增加，其价格已大幅下降。闪存 ROM 现在几乎完全取代了 EEPROM，甚至正在蚕食 EPROM 和 PROM 的领地。闪存 ROM 的可擦除性、相对速度和高容量等优势使其成为一种几乎理想的通用永久存储芯片。

                                                                                                                Flash ROMs were originally much more expensive than EEPROMs, which were, in turn, more expensive than EPROMs, and so on. The price of flash chips has come down considerably in the 10 years or so since they were first developed because their volume has increased. Flash ROMs have now almost entirely replaced EEPROMs and are even encroaching on EPROM and PROM territory. The advantages of flash ROM's erasability, relative speed, and high volume make it nearly ideal as an all-purpose permanent memory chip.

                                                                                                                  易失性 RAM

                                                                                                                  Volatile RAM

                                                                                                                  除了 ROM 之外，另一大类内存芯片是 RAM。RAM 芯片存储数据位的方式与 ROM 芯片类似，但有两个主要区别：RAM 芯片几乎可以即时擦除和重新编程，并且存储在 RAM 芯片中的数据不是永久性的。RAM 芯片在断电后会“忘记”它们存储的所有内容。RAM 芯片用于需要大量短期内存存储的计算机和其他产品。

                                                                                                                  The other major category of memory chips besides ROMs is RAMs. RAM chips store data bits just like ROM chips do, but with two major differences: RAM chips can be erased and reprogrammed almost instantaneously and the data stored in RAM chips is not permanent. RAM chips "forget" everything they're storing when you turn off their electricity. RAM chips are used in computers and other products that need lots of short-term memory storage.

                                                                                                                  RAM 芯片几乎在所有方面都不如 ROM 芯片，但它们是必需的，因为它们的工作方式类似于电子暂存器。即使是闪存 ROM 芯片也需要很长时间才能擦除和重新使用，因此不适合用作计算机的主存储器。RAM 芯片比 ROM 芯片更贵，也更难使用，但它们是最受欢迎的内存芯片类型。每台新 PC 的价格在一定程度上取决于制造计算机时 RAM 芯片的现货价格。

                                                                                                                  RAM chips are inferior to ROM chips in almost every way, yet they are necessary because they work like electronic scratchpads. Even flash ROM chips take far too much time to erase and reuse to be practical for the main memory in a computer. RAM chips are more expensive and harder to use than ROM chips, but they're the most popular kind of memory chips made. The price of every new PC is determined, in part, by the spot price of RAM chips when the computer was built.

                                                                                                                  RAM 芯片有两种基本类型：SRAM 和 DRAM。首字母 S 和 D 分别代表静态 RAM 和动态 RAM。这两种描述对我们来说都不是特别有用，甚至术语 RAM 也令人困惑。随机访问是指计算机可以以随机顺序访问存储在 RAM 芯片中的任何位。例如，它不必按顺序读出位，就像从头到尾观看录像带一样。RAM 芯片可以随时随机提供任何位的数据。

                                                                                                                  RAM chips come in two basic types: SRAM and DRAM. The initial S and D stand for static and dynamic RAM, respectively. Neither description is particularly useful to us here, and even the term RAM is confusing. Random-access is meant to indicate that a computer can access any bit stored in a RAM chip in random order. For example, it doesn't have to read out the bits in sequence, like watching a videotape from start to finish. RAM chips can provide any bit of data at any time, randomly.

                                                                                                                  老实说，ROM 芯片也可以随机读取数据，因此 RAM 根本不能准确描述它们之间的区别。读写存储器 (RWM) 更具描述性，但发音更困难。

                                                                                                                  Honestly, ROM chips can also read out data randomly, so RAM doesn't accurately describe the difference between them at all. Read-write memory (RWM) would be more descriptive, but harder to pronounce.

                                                                                                                  静态存储器

                                                                                                                  SRAM

                                                                                                                  SRAM 芯片设计更简单，运行时耗电量更少，制造成本更低，而且速度比 DRAM 更快。然而，除了所有这些优点之外，SRAM 还有一个主要缺点：它们只能存储 DRAM 芯片大约四分之一的数据位。SRAM 和 DRAM 的容量逐年增加，但 SRAM 总是比 DRAM 低四倍。正因为如此，SRAM 通常只用于使用小型电池（SRAM 的效率很重要）或需要非常快的产品。

                                                                                                                  SRAM chips are simpler to design, use less electricity in operation, cost less to manufacture, and are faster than DRAM. Overshadowing all these advantages, however, SRAMs have one major drawback: They can only store about one-quarter as many data bits as a DRAM chip. The capacity of both SRAMs and DRAMs increases year by year, but SRAMs are always a factor of four behind their DRAM cousins. Because of that, SRAMs are generally used only in products that run on small batteries (where SRAM's efficiency is valuable) or those that need to be very fast.

                                                                                                                  与 ROM 芯片不同，SRAM 芯片存储数据和检索数据一样容易。事实上，它们存储数据的速度比检索数据的速度稍快。这使得 SRAM 芯片对于非常快速的计算机非常重要。它们还用于微处理器芯片内的指令缓存和数据缓存。可擦除 ROM 可能每月擦除一次并用新数据重新编程，但 SRAM 每秒存储新数据数千次。SRAM 也不必像 EPROM 那样一次性擦除。它们可以更改一位数据，同时保持数百万其他位完好无损。

                                                                                                                  Unlike ROM chips, SRAM chips can store data as easily as they retrieve it. In fact, they can store data slightly faster than they retrieve it. This makes SRAM chips important for very fast computers. They are also used for the instruction cache and data cache inside microprocessor chips. An erasable ROM might be erased and reprogrammed with new data once per month, but SRAMs store new data thousands of times per second. SRAMs don't have to be erased all at once like EPROMs, either. They can change one bit of data while holding millions of other bits intact.

                                                                                                                  动态随机存取记忆体

                                                                                                                  DRAM

                                                                                                                  DRAM 是整个内存芯片市场的销量领导者。计算机制造商和许多消费电子产品大量使用 DRAM，因为它们具有最大的存储容量。SRAM 芯片可能速度更快、耗能更少，但 DRAM 是获得大量可擦除内存的最便宜方式。

                                                                                                                  DRAMs are the volume leader of the entire memory chip market. Computer makers and many consumer electronics products use DRAMs in enormous quantities because they have the greatest storage capacity for the money.
